<html>
<head>
<title>Buckley: Has the WTO Threatened Us? -- 1/23/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<i>
New York, January 23, 1996
</i>

<h2>
Has the WTO Threatened Us?
</h2>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/
buckley
.html">
William F. Buckley Jr.
</a>

<P>
Well, it happened: the World Trade Organization ruled against an 
existing law, and people are up in arms. Candidates Dole and Buchanan 
have suggested that this is on the order of the British navy moving in 
to restore the crown as sovereign in U.S. affairs.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Here is the quarrel. Brazil and Venezuela, in recent months, attempted 
to bring into the United States what we might as well call "dirty 
oil," meaning that it is oil that contains a higher density of 
pollutants than is permitted by the Clean Air Act. So, we denied that 
oil access to the American market. 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
A suit was filed with the WTO by Brazil and Venezuela, which asserted, 
correctly, that the same quality of oil turned down at our frontier 
was in fact being pumped, sold, and burned within the United States. 
This is, plain and simple, discriminatory, and of course the General 
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade exists in order to protest 
discriminatory practices.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Now the United States has several defenses, none of them conclusive -- 
they are an attenuation of the violation rather than an excuse for it. 
It happens that the load of oil being permitted to market 
notwithstanding its high pollution content was something on the order 
of an exception. The franchise was given with a view to saving a 
considerable deposit of oil, on the understanding that the 
international standard would be invoked beginning in 1998. 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Now if one engages in a treaty of this kind there has to be an arbiter 
somewhere. The disarmament treaties of the Twenties and Thirties 
failed for many reasons, but one of them was that there was no 
effective tribunal to call attention to the violations of Germany, 
Italy, and Japan. For that reason, a court was set up, armed with the 
power to make a finding (subject to appeal) and to levy either a fine, 
if the situation was not rectifiable, or else compensation (to the 
wounded nation or industry). The court, having ruled against the 
United States, has not come through with a specified penalty, and in 
any event, this being the very first ruling the WTO has come through 
with, there is abounding procedural confusion. 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
One source of the confusion is the motives and political interests of 
the people involved, directly and indirectly. Mickey Kantor is of 
course our trade representative. He is having a hell of a time. On the 
one hand, he very much wants to defend the environmental code approved 
by President Clinton, which means, No dirty oil. On the other hand, he 
desperately wishes to be outside the line of fire directed against 
those who tolerate an extra-national body telling the United States 
what to do. To date, Mr. Kantor has said that in fact the court is 
factually correct; that the court has no right, really, to rule on 
U.S. environmental laws; and that the United States will appeal -- 
probably. 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Now the long perspective on the question is that the GATT treaty was a 
dozen years in formation, under the Reagan, Bush, and Clinton 
Administrations, with the Congress as a prime mover. Our motives were 
simple: most trade discrimination in the world is against U.S. 
producers. We have, we thought, and thought correctly, more to gain 
than to lose by endorsing a court that could actually hand down 
rulings of the kind that free up trade. 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Bob Dole and Pat Buchanan are talking about the hideous nature of an 
extra-national authority, and Mr. Buchanan even said that when he 
became President, the first thing he would do is repeal the GATT 
treaty. But the U.S. position is made difficult by the simple fact 
that a) we promoted and passed the GATT agreement (while avoiding the 
treaty requirement to come in with two-thirds of the Senate vote), 
endorsing b) a fact-finding body (the court) that would look into 
complaints and c) dispose of sanctions in the event a signatory was 
found guilty of discriminatory practices.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
We now have several alternatives. We can resign from GATT, which would 
be a long-term invitation to restricted trading; or we can pay the 
fine or compensation on the Brazilian and Venezuelan oil; or we can 
modify the Clean Air Act to exempt the privileged producer of the 
dirty oil. 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
What we can't do is argue that somebody took away our lollipop. We are 
a grown-up nation, and if we pulled a fast one at the expense of a law 
we ourselves promoted and ratified, then we should take the 
punishment. If ever the WTO engages in systematic anti-U.S. rulings, 
why it becomes simple. We pull out. But not before that happens.

<p>
<p>


</blockquote></blockquote>


<br><center>
[<a href ="/townhall/columnists/"> Columnists </a>]

<br>[<a href ="/nationalreview/"> National Review </a> ]
<P>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map">
<img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0">
</a></center>
<P>
</body>
