<html>
<head>
<title>Nightmare Time</title>
</head>
<center>

</center>
<p>
<p>

<i><center>New York August 4th</i><hr>
<h2>Nightmare Time</h2>
<p>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/buckley.html"><i>William F. Buckley Jr.</i></a>
<hr></center>
<p>
The sudden thrust by the Croatians at the expense of neighboring Serbs tells us not very much that there is armed life in the area and that finally something stoexcept pped what was appearing to be a Blitzkrieg by Bosnian Serbs. Their objective has been, for four years, Sarajevo.  Collateral triumphs have been the discrediting of the United Nations, NATO, and U.S. foreign policy.
<p>
The break in America from the isolation of yesteryear was the result of the reduction from thirty days to thirty minutes of the traversability of the space that had shielded America from Europe for four centuries. The principled arguments -- revisionist but nonetheless convincing -- against our entry into the First World War were decreasingly safe when used to oppose our entry into the Second 
World War. It is of course a hackneyed irony to remark that Sarajevo triggered the First World War and is now a point of conflagration that could trigger, if not a world war, a collapse of the scaffolding we 
hoped to build in the postwar years. 
<p>
The primary cause of disillusion with world-mindedness after the Second World War was the diplomatic defeats we suffered in Europe and then in Asia. Having joined the Allies in a mission initiated to restore sovereignty to Poland, we were maneuvered into the totalitarian desolation of much of Europe under Stalin. At the other end of the world, having triumphed over imperialist Japan we stood by helpless against the Communization of China under Mao Tse-tung. To say the least, this damaged the sensibilities of those Americans who dreamed of making the world safe for democracy. But a further and protracted jolt was the formation of the United Nations. Not that the idea of an international body was wrong, but that the UN became almost overnight the diplomatic ganglion of hypocrisy. There the Soviet Union dominated the votes of the Third World. After jubilation over the retreat of British imperialism in India, Americans stood shocked and aghast when Pandit Nehru refused to condemn the Soviet tanks that gunned down students in Budapest who sought a few scraps of liberty. 
The United Nations, in short, didn't work, and indeed sheltered the most impudent rhetorical hypocrisies in diplomatic history. 
<p>
After the Nuremberg trials the civilized world seemed to be united on at least one proposition, namely that genocide would not again be tolerated. Well, it was tolerated. When it happened in Africa we 
managed discreet sighs and, in the closet, whispered that civilization had yet to reach certain parts of the world. But then with the end of Communism a refreshment of international idealism temporarily took 
over. The UN, for one thing, would no longer serve as an echo chamber for Soviet lies and hypocrisy. Then along came Yugoslavia, RIP.
<p>
There to the north, northeast, and west loomed the mighty power of Russia, Germany, France, and England. Diplomatic efforts to arrest ethnic cleansing crystallize as games concocted to engage the 
attention of students at war colleges. In the background geographically, in the foreground geopolitically, was the United States. On the one hand it was clearly the burden of Europe to handle 
the mess in Yugoslavia. On the other hand, we were the undisputed superpower, and it turned out that we could not breathe the requisite concern into our NATO allies. And so, month after month, year after 
year, nothing is done except that people kill each other and latent hostilities are stimulated. There is the Serb affinity for Russians and vice versa, the Western European historical affinity for Croatia. 
The Muslim world correctly questions whether there is any reliable concern in Europe for aggressions at its expense. The Greeks watch nervously at movement in the other Macedonia, and the Turks, however frequently they are reminded of their own historical excesses, let it be known that they are brothers of the Bosnians being killed, tortured, raped.
<p>
In New Jersey if year after year a county can't manage its own schools, Trenton takes the schools over. The metaphor is easily resisted: How exactly does NATO take over Belgrade? But that is the 
wrong approach in a century in which the question, How do we split an atom? was answered: We shall proceed to do so. 
<p>
The NATO enterprise is discredited. The Europeans are mired in their spiritual trough, and the feeling in America is, more and more: Two hot wars and one cold war are enough for one century. You figure it 
out.  Unhappily, history won't stand by to permit us our alienation. The reason we are entangled in Europe -- and in the Pacific -- is that we can't escape the consequences of  what happens there.
<p>

[<a href="/townhall/columnists/welcome.html.cgi">Columnists</a>]<br>
[<a href="/nationalreview/welcome.html">National Review</a>]<br><p>
</body>
</html>
