<html>

<head>

<title>Buckley:  Understanding the Papal Bull</title>

</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">

<center>

<i>NEW YORK, OCTOBER 10</i>

<hr>

<h2>Understanding the Papal Bull</h2><br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/buckley.html"><b><i>William F. Buckley Jr.</i></b></a><hr><br></center>



The impression made by Pope John Paul was quite simply stunning. 
Granted, the panoply was intoxicatingly splendid; yet all those 
millions of candles and choirboys and bishops would not have given the 
spectator such life as he got from what he saw and heard if its 
centerpiece had been a nice old bore. The transfiguring feature of all 
those appearances was the man, and his words. "May the Holy Spirit 
strengthen your hearts, making them blameless and holy before our God 
and Father, so that you may serve His people with ever greater joy." 
We are not talking about sound bites.
                                                            <P>
But one needs to be reminded that the exhortations of a pope are 
customarily done in the paradigmatic mode, which is fitting for the 
primary spokesman for Biblical injunctions. The language of Moses and 
of Christ is totalist in its formulation. We are enjoined to be -- 
saintly.
                                            <P>
This is beyond the reach of all but the very few. Even so, what we 
hear said about how we should be cannot be attenuated by the 
foreknowledge of man's inability to attain perfection. Give everything 
you have to the poor and join the pilgrimage of Christ -- here is a 
rock-solid injunction, toward the discharge of which human efforts are 
almost necessarily asymptotic. States are the organs of individuals, 
and so one runs into difficulties translating Christian imperatives 
into social policy. This is a problem that every pope in this century 
has faced, and Pope John Paul II cannot solve it, perhaps because it 
cannot be solved.
                            <P>
It has frequently been noticed that papal declarations tend to be 
undernourished on the matter of production. The emphasis is almost 
always on distribution. Thus we hear from papal declarations dating 
back more than one century about the obligation of the rich to give to 
the poor. The question naturally arises: It is right for Wealthy John 
to give to Poor Peter, but do we translate this into an obligation by 
John to vote to instruct Internal Revenue to descend on Wealthy James, 
to give to Poor Peter? The incorporation of individual virtue into 
state policy is a difficult business.
                 <P>
Consider the question of immigration. The Pope said, shortly after 
landing, "America keeps compassion, generosity and concern for others 
at the very heart of its efforts. . . . From the beginning until now, 
the United States has been a haven for generation after generation of 
new arrivals. Men, women, and children have streamed here from every 
corner of the globe, building new lives and forming a society of rich 
ethnic and racial diversity based on commitment to a shared vision of 
human dignity and freedom."
  <P>
Now this is not accurate historical accounting. What it is is a 
sublimation of American history. It is American history as it would be 
recounted if Americans were all saints -- and if no grass ever grew to 
interrupt the waterflow of goodness.
                                                                              <P>
What is true is that American compassion has been marked and still is: 
50 per cent of the world's immigration to the developed countries is 
into the United States. But it is also true that several times in 
American history Congress has elected to limit, or even to suspend, 
immigration. Sometimes the motivations of individual congressmen are 
xenophobic -- they just don't want any more foreigners. The Oriental 
Exclusion Act was quite straightforward on this matter.
                                                               <P>
But sometimes, also, practical considerations were at the forefront of 
legislative action. During the Depression it would hardly have made 
sense to invite a large wave of immigrants into a country in which 
millions were suffering and 20 per cent were unemployed. And then the 
question arises today: Is it a trespass on Christian principles to 
advocate a temporary restriction in the current rate of immigration? 
Is Barbara Jordan -- who headed the commission that recommended 
exactly that -- anti-Christian?
                                               <P>
Manifestly, it isn't so. Yet to advocate reduced immigration isn't to 
fault the Pope for speaking in the language of prophets, who deal not, 
and should not deal, with such questions as: Is California going broke 
under the burden? Is multiculturalism breaking up our culture? Why are 
there national borders, if immigration is not properly a matter of 
government policy?
                                   <P>
What we are left with is the papal injunction to: compassion, 
generosity, and concern for others. The particularization of those 
sentiments is necessarily a problem for individual states.
<p>

<br>
<center>
[<a href ="/townhall/columnists/welcome.html.cgi"> Other Columns </a>]

<br>[<a href ="/nationalreview/welcome.html"> National Review </a>]

<br>
