</DOCHDR>
<html><title>Buckley:  The Inside War -- 12/22/95</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<center>
<i>NEW YORK, DECEMBER 22</i>
<hr>
<h2>The Inside War</h2><br>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/buckley.html"><b><i>William F. Buckley Jr.</i></b></a><hr><br></center>
<P>

The sequence is roughly as follows:
<P>
1. Senator Dole makes a statement: He will not, in 1996, urge the GOP 
to endorse a constitutional amendment that would ban the practice of 
abortion. 
<P>
Buzz . . . Why is Bob doing this? He needs the right wing of his party 
to get nominated . . . No, stupid, he is thinking about the election 
now. He has already won the nomination. He is following Nixon's rule: 
Woo the Right in order to be nominated, the Left in order to be 
elected. 
<P>
2. Ralph Reed, the Executive Director of the Christian Coalition, 
fires immediately. "Senator Dole's remarks not only represent an 
uncharacteristic departure from his previous record, but a stunning 
reversal from the winning Reagan position that has sustained the 
Republican Party for 15 years and helped make it a majority party. Not 
a single pro-life incumbent of either political party lost in 1994 and 
1995. Senator Dole is also the only leading candidate who has declined 
to sign a pledge that he supports the pro-life plank in the Republican 
Party platform." 
<P>
The sentence of the court was duly executed: "The Christian Coalition 
will distribute 22 million voter guides in the presidential primaries 
next winter and spring. Those voter guides will accurately reflect 
Senator Dole's and other candidates' positions on this issue." The 
next day, the Dole campaign "clarified" its candidate's remarks.
<P>
3. Noemie Emery ("a freelance writer living in New York") writes a 
lead article for The Weekly Standard. Early in its career, The 
Standard published an eloquent editorial affirming the pro-life 
position. Miss Emery says in effect, Look. Though we rightly consider 
the fetus a human being, it is something less than that exactly, and 
under the circumstances different moral perspectives are 
understandably brought to bear on the question, and the GOP should 
drop its categorical position and settle, instead, for progressive 
restrictions, leading in the right direction. 
<P>
Irving Kristol, a few days later, in an eloquent article in the Wall 
Street Journal berating the excesses of modern secularists, then asks, 
What are the mistakes of the other side? There are several. "Whatever 
one's views on abortion, it is clear that public opinion, today and 
for the foreseeable future, will not accept its criminalization." He 
upbraids his fellow conservatives: "By permitting their passions to 
dominate the issue, by converting their commitment to a 'right to 
life' crusade rather than to policy, they have made the best the enemy 
of the good -- a common error of zealotry in politics."
<P>
4. NATIONAL REVIEW sees in the Emery article a "part of a continuing 
effort to revise the Republican platform. Last year conservatives 
William Kristol and George Weigel suggested in NATIONAL REVIEW that 
pro-lifers focus on more readily achievable objectives such as 
parental-consent laws or bans on third-trimester abortions. Pro-lifers 
could debate the prudence of this position within the context of 
shared objectives: a reduction in the number of abortions and legal 
recognition of the practice's injustice." 
<P>
But the editors make two points, one of them transcendent in 
character: "Miss Emery and Mr. Bennett would reach a different 
judgment on abortion, and the reason is plain to everyone but them: 
they evidently do not regard abortion as 'wrong' in the same sense 
that infanticide is wrong." And a most telling empirical political 
point: If the strategic design of the pro-lifers is to win the fight 
with progressive tactical strikes, they are entitled to ask, "Where is 
a comparable modesty or prudence on the other side? Where is the 
willingness, on the part of Senators Kennedy and Specter, to accept 
restraints even on a handful of abortions, such as the grisly 'partial 
birth' abortions? The fact of the matter is that Noemie Emery and 
William Bennett have no audience on the pro-choice side. The pro-
choicers will not concede even the slightest restriction on abortion, 
because any restriction implies its wrongness." 
<P>
Kremlinologists can divert themselves by reflecting that William 
Kristol was a trustee of NATIONAL REVIEW until he became the 
(founding) editor of The Standard, that he is the son of Irving 
Kristol, that William Bennett was for several years a Senior Editor of 
NATIONAL REVIEW, that Bennett -- and Kennedy! -- are both Catholics, 
that George Weigel is a theologically trained Catholic, that Ralph 
Reed and Bob Dole are Protestants, the Kristols Jewish: and, of 
course, all of them Republicans. Just one more example of hegemonic 
conservative thought.<p>

<br><center>

[<a href ="/townhall/columnists/"> Columnists </a>]

<br>[<a href ="/nationalreview/"> National Review </a> ]

<br>
<br>
