<html><head><title>Chavez:  'Dynamic' Newest Banned Word --1/4/96
</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>




<center><i>January 10, 1996</i>
<hr>
<h2>'Dynamic' Newest Banned Word</h2><a href="/townhall/columnists/chavez.html">Linda Chavez</a></center>
<p><hr><P> 
 

Bethesda, Md. - Warning: Radical feminists have added a new word to 
their lexicon of forbidden terms. "Dynamic" now joins "seminal," 
"mankind" and "hysterical" among other "sexist" expressions that 
feminists want to expunge from our vocabularies.
<P>
This most recent skirmish in the feminist language war erupted at 
Chico State University in California, where the philosophy department 
recently advertised for "a dynamic classroom teacher and program 
builder" to teach the "philosophy of feminism." The ad drew fire from 
a feminist English professor and the university's affirmative action 
director, who charged that the word "dynamic" described a "kinetic, 
dramatic style" most often associated with white males. University 
administrators, not wanting to offend, rewrote the ad, substituting 
"excellent" for "dynamic," but the controversy didn't end there. The 
local newspaper put the story on Page One, and even the usually 
liberal San Francisco Chronicle editorialized against adding "dynamic" 
to "the growing list of socially unacceptable words."
<P>
The whole episode might be amusing if it weren't part of a serious - 
and successful - propaganda campaign to change not only the way we 
talk but also the way we thingk. As George Orwell noted 50 years ago 
in his famous essay "Politics and the English Language". "If thought 
corrupts language, language can also corrupt thought." And corrupting 
thought is what radical feminism is all about.
<P>
Feminists fully understand their mission. "The political implications 
of language have made linguistic study imperative for feminists," 
intones the Women's Study Encyclopedia in an essay on "Feminism and 
Semiological Theory." For those uninitiated in contemporary academic 
jargon, semiotics is a theory of language that asserts that words are 
symbols representing not only the things they describe but, more 
importantly, the values of the dominant class within a culture. If you 
wnat to change the values of a culture, you must change its language. 
And feminists have been trying to change ours for a generation.
<P>
We've all but abandoned sex-specific terms in public usage. Firemen 
and policemen have disappeared, even though they account for 98% of 
fire department personnel and 84% of those in police departments. Miss 
and Mrs. have given way to the nondescript and dissonant Ms. Official 
Washington has banished its chairmen and spokesmen. And most editors 
would rather break grammar rules than offend feminists, substituting 
"they" for the generic "he" when a third person singular pronoun is 
required. (One copy editor actually suggested that I use the pronoun 
"it" when referring to a non-specific child.) Even "mother" and 
"father" are becomng endangered terms, replaced by the less 
descriptive "parent."
<P>
Sex itself is being quickly supplanted by "gender" - which in 
feministspeak refers to an arbitrary social construct. As the Women's 
Study Encyclopedia puts it: "To many, gender continues to be read as 
synonymous with sex." But not to radical feminists, for whom "the 
relation between sex and gender has becmoe the central question for 
contemporary feminist theory as a whole." The idea is to abolish 
differences between men and wom,en, even those rooted in nature. And 
the first step is to break down distinctions in language - to 
"deconstruct" language, in another favorite phrase from the jargon of 
the academic left.
<P>
Author and philosophy professor Christina Hoff Sommers, whose book 
"Who Stole Feminism?" is a biting critique of radical feminists on 
campus, makes the distinction between what she calls "gender 
feminists" and "equity feminists." The former see themselves as 
victims of a culture totally dominated by men, and their objective is 
to transform that culture, using language as a tool to reconstruct 
society in their image.
<P>
"Equity feminists," on the other hand, simply want women to have equal 
legal rights with men and the same opportunities as men to make the 
most of their own individual talents. Unfortunately, the gender 
feminists have the upper hand in universities across the country, and 
their influence spills over into the broader culture day by day.

The attempt to neuter language, or to put certain words off limits 
because they ostensibly represent masculine traits, is an exercise in 
thought control. Totalitarianism didn't disappear with the collapse of 
the Soviet Union. It's alive and well on many American college 
campuses today. 
<P>
<center><hr width="50%">



<i>Linda Chavez is president of the Center for Equal Opportunity.<br>
<p>Contact <a href="mailto:lchavezusa@aol.com">Linda Chavez</a></i>.<p><center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map">
<img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a>

</center>
</body>


