<html> 
<head> 
<title>Chavez: Minimum wage: Bad idea GOP fears to fight  - 4/24/96 
 -- 03/27/96 
</title> 
</head> 
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"> 
<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE> 
<a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a><p><br>
<i>   March 24, 1996</i><br> 
<h2> 
Minimum wage: Bad idea GOP fears to fight 
</h2> 
 
 
<a href="/townhall/columnistsavez.html"> 
Linda Chavez 
</a> 
 
<P>   
 
HEADLINE: Minimum wage: Bad idea GOP fears to fight 
 
BETHESDA, Md. -- Republicans may as well run a white flag up the 
Capitol flagpole if the current debate over a minimum-wage hike is any 
indication of their resolve to retain congressional power this fall. 
The Republican leadership seems to have given up even trying to make 
the case against raising the minimum wage. The leaders know the 
Democrats' proposal to increase the federal minimum wage 20% over two 
years, to $ 5.15 per hour, is bad policy, but they're scared to death 
of the politics of the issue. 
 <BR>  
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
That's why 24 moderate Republicans have already broken ranks with the 
leadership and offered their own -- higher -- minimum-wage bill. 
 <BR>  
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
But sacrificing policy to politics is usually a bad bargain, even in 
an election year. 
 <BR>  
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
There's no question that raising the minimum wage is popular. Recent 
polls show that about 8 in 10 voters favor the proposed increase. Most 
people can't imagine living on the current $ 4.25 an hour minimum, 
much less supporting a family on such low wages. 
 <BR>  
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
And rightfully so, since so few workers actually do support themselves 
or families at minimum-wage jobs. 
 <BR>  
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
Of the approximately 2 million workers -- out of a national workforce 
of nearly 140 million -- who earn $ 4.25 or less an hour, 53% are 
younger than 25 years of age. Most minimum-wage workers today are 
secondary earners who come from middle-class families, often students 
who work part time. 
 <BR>  
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
Almost as many current minimum-wage workers live in families earning 
more than $ 50,000 a year as live in poor households. 
<BR>  
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;  
Of course, increasing the minimum by 90 cents an hour will enlarge the 
universe of minimum-wage workers, covering an additional 8 million 
workers who earn up to $ 5.15 an hour, many of whom are older and more 
likely to support families. 
<BR>  
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;  
But it won't necessarily improve their economic opportunities. Most 
economists agree that raising the minimum wage will cost jobs; the 
only real question is how many. 
<BR>  
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;  
Secretary of Labor Robert Reich has been touting a couple of studies 
that dispute decades of research in this area, most notably a study 
involving fast-food restaurants in New Jersey and California by 
Princeton economists David Card and Alan Krueger (who served for a 
while as Reich's chief economist). The Card/Krueger study purported to 
show that New Jersey's state minimum-wage hike to $ 5.05 per hour, one 
of the highest in the nation, did not lead to job losses. But the 
study now has been largely discounted by everyone but its authors and 
Reich. 
 <BR>  
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
The New Jersey findings were based on data obtained from carelessly 
worded telephone surveys and were subsequently disproved by other 
economists who examined actual payroll records in the state. 
<BR>  
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;  
Nonetheless, most Republicans have been intimidated into silence. The 
best the leadership now hopes for is to attach the proposal to 
legislation Republicans want and Democrats don't, thereby either 
sinking the bill or exacting a price for its passage. 
<BR>  
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;  
Perhaps the most cynical political move of all, however, came from the 
24 maverick House Republicans who last week announced their own bill 
to increase the federal minimum wage to $ 5.25 an hour. Most of them 
come from high-wage states in the Northeast with tight labor markets 
where it is almost impossible to hire someone at the minimum wage. 
<BR>  
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;  
These states have been losing jobs to lower-wage states in the South 
and West for years. 
 But if Congress increases the minimum wage nationally, these states 
won't be at such a competitive disadvantage. What these Republican 
legislators seem to be saying (if not in so many words) is that if 
their districts must lose jobs, why not share the pain? 
<BR>  
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;  
Republicans have nothing to gain by backing a minimum-wage increase -- 
and a lot to lose. 
 <BR>  
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
If the Republicans cave on this issue, it will cost jobs -- including, 
no doubt, those of some Republican members of Congress who will have shown they lack the courage of their own convictions. 
<BR>  
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 

<P><P> 
<HR> 
<P> 
 
<i> 
<center> 
Linda Chavez is president of the Center for Equal Opportunity.<br> 
<p>Contact <a href="mailto:lchavezusa@aol.com">Linda Chavez</a>. 
 
</i> 
 
</blockquote></blockquote>  
 
 
