<html>  
<head>  
<title>Chavez: All Hail Shift From Racial Numbers Game  - 5/01/96  
</title>  
</head>  
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">  
  
<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>  
 
<i>   May 1, 1996</i><br>  
  
  
  
<h2>  
All Hail Shift From Racial Numbers Game  
</h2>


<a href="/townhall/columnists/chavez.html">  
Linda Chavez  
</a>  
  
<P>    
 
BETHESDA, Md. -- Proponents of affirmative action and forced busing  
are complaining of an ominous shift away from support for civil  
rights. They point to recent court rulings and state and national  
efforts to bar preferences for minorities as proof the mood has turned  
ugly. A recent cover of Time even warned the country is headed "Back  
to segregation" on the eve of the 100th anniversary of Plessy vs.  
Ferguson, the Supreme Court's infamous 1896 "separate but equal"  
ruling.  
<BR>   
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;  
What's really going on is the repudiation of the racial numbers game  
invoked to end discrimination. Americans overwhelmingly support the  
right of minorities to attend the same schools and compete for the  
same jobs as whites. The National Opinion Research Center, which has  
been monitoring opinion on racial issues for more than 50 years,  
reports that 90% of Americans favor such rights.  
<BR>   
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;  
That doesn't mean they're willing to go along with schemes to bus  
schoolchildren or give hiring preferences to minorities to maintain  
some ideal "racial balance." Debates in Massachusetts and California  
illustrate the current mood.  
<BR>   
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;  
For years, Massachusetts has been trying to enforce racial balance in  
the public schools. A 22-year-old state law declares any school with a  
minority enrollment that exceeds 50% is out of balance. Under the law,  
districts that "voluntarily" balance their schools' racial composition  
through busing or other methods receive a huge financial bonus. The  
state covers 90% of the cost of school construction for districts that  
comply, an incentive critics have called a virtual bribe.  
<BR>   
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;  
Now, however, the state board of education is considering repealing  
the law. And the most vociferous proponent of repeal is Abigail  
Thernstrom, a soft-spoken political scientist with impeccable civil  
rights credentials.  
<BR>   
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;  
California, too, has been in the forefront of the racial numbers game,  
especially in higher education. A University of California medical  
school was the focus of the Supreme Court's famous 1978 Bakke  
decision, which barred outright admissions quotas by race but allowed  
schools to "take race into account" in order to promote "diversity."  
Last summer, however, the university's regents voted to prohibit any  
racial or ethnic preferences in admissions or hiring. And leading the  
charge was Ward Connerly, a black businessman who now heads the effort  
to enact a ban on all state preferences.  
<BR>   
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;  
Neither move indicates the clock is being turned back on civil rights  
enforcement. What they do signify is an end to a fixation with racial  
balance as an end in itself. That obsession did little to improve the  
quality of education for black or white children or to improve the  
skills of minority workers.  
<BR>   
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;  
In his book Forced Justice, David Armor points out that the gap  
between white and black educational achievement has been closing over  
the past few decades, but it has little to do with school  
desegregation. According to Armor's assessment of national data,  
"Gains for segregated black students are as large or larger than for  
desegregated blacks, and . . . blacks in disadvantaged urban  
communities gain as much as blacks in nondisadvantaged communities."  
Armor maintains that black students' achievement has much more to do  
with their parents' economic status than their classmates' color, just  
like whites.  
<BR>   
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;  
Simply trying to balance numbers by race and ethnicity won't improve  
the quality of schools children attend or help them gain the skills  
necessary to compete later in life. But a shift away from numbers  
might actually force policymakers to deal with the true impediments to  
minority progress.  
<BR>   
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;  
 
<P><P>  
<HR>  
<P>  
  
<i>  
<center>  
Linda Chavez is president of the Center for Equal Opportunity.<br>  
<p>Contact <a href="mailto:lchavezusa@aol.com">Linda Chavez</a>.  
  
</i>  
  
</blockquote></blockquote>   
  
  
<P> <br><center>  
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map">  
<img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0">  
</a></center>  
