</DOCHDR>
<html>     
<head>     
<title>Chavez: Market, Not Politics, Drives Gas Prices  -- 5/08/96     
</title>     
</head>     
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">     
     
<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>     
    
<i>   May 8, 1996</i><br>     
     
     
     
<h2>     
Market, Not Politics, Drives Gas Prices  <br>   
</h2>     
     
     
<a href="/townhall/columnists/chavez.html">    
Linda Chavez     
</a>     
     
<P>       
 If Americans want big, fancy cars, they have to pay the price.     
 <p> 
BETHESDA, Md. -- Looking for someone to blame for today's high gas     
prices? Chances are the culprits aren't some oil executives in Houston     
or sheiks in Riyadh, but a lot closer to home.     
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;     
Try looking in your own garage or your neighbor's. Minivans, sport     
utility vehicles and pickup trucks are fast replacing compacts as     
Americans' favorite vehicles. These bigger cars, plus higher speed     
limits, have driven down fuel efficiency and driven up demand.     
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;     
So, too, did last winter's bitter cold, which kept consumers burning     
more heating oil in their furnaces. Just last week, snow once again     
hit the Rocky Mountains and the Midwest, creating more home heating     
oil demand long past the usual season. And unless supply can keep pace     
with demand -- which is difficult in the short run for a product like     
gasoline -- the price goes up. It's as close to a fixed law of     
economics as there is.     
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;     
But politicians can't very well blame their own constituents or Mother     
Nature for rising prices at the pumps, so they're playing politics --     
on both sides of the aisle. The Clinton administration announced plans     
to sell off part of the Strategic Petroleum Reserve. This move is     
probably harmless, if ineffectual, since it will add a mere trickle     
into the consumers' supply, about 12 million barrels or less than two     
days' worth of gas for the nation's drivers.     
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;     
But the administration didn't stop there. The Justice Department also     
announced it will investigate the oil companies for collusion and     
price-fixing. This is nothing more than a cynical attempt to win votes     
by peddling paranoia.     
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;     
Meanwhile, the Republicans have been exploiting the gasoline pricing     
issue for their own purposes. They're using recent price hikes to     
justify repealing a tax they've been opposed to from its inception:     
the Clinton administration's 4.3-cent-per-gallon gas tax. Cutting     
taxes is a good thing, but no one should be under any illusion that     
repealing the gas tax will have any permanent effect on the price of     
gasoline.     
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;     
One of the biggest dangers in this political posturing is that it     
feeds the all-too-common misconception that government intervention in     
the economy can work to benefit consumers. It never happens that way.     
Even if the president or Congress could wave a magic wand and cut     
prices, government price controls lead to supply shortages. Would     
Americans really rather line up for hours at filling stations than pay     
a few cents more per gallon?     
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;     
In fact, although prices have risen steeply recently -- 13% in three     
months -- gasoline is still a great bargain in the United States.     
Europeans and Asians pay four times as much for their gas as we do,     
which is why they drive smaller, more fuel-efficient cars. And the     
American Petroleum Institute says we are actually paying the lowest     
price per gallon, in constant dollars, since World War I.     
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;     
But although we're paying less, we're using more gasoline than ever.     
We now live farther from work and shopping than we once did. And wives     
as well as husbands commute to work, often in separate cars from their     
spouses. All that adds up to more miles on the road.     
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;     
Dr. Lee Shipper, a researcher at Lawrence Berkeley Laboratory in     
California, estimated in The New York Times recently that U.S.     
vehicles traveled 7,900 miles per person in 1994, compared with 5,350     
in 1973. More fuel-efficient cars in recent years helped reduce the     
impact of these longer distances. But in 1994, bigger vehicles brought     
fuel efficiency down once again to 19.3 miles per gallon from a high     
of 20.2 in 1985.     
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;     
Prices will probably decline somewhat in the weeks and months ahead as     
supply catches up with demand -- especially if Iraq re-enters the     
market, as it is expected to if Saddam Hussein agrees to terms imposed     
by the U=2EN. with U.S. backing.     
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;     
But so long as Americans want the freedom to drive our own big, fancy     
vehicles long distances for work and play, we're going to have to pay     
the price.     
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;     
    
<P><P>     
<HR>     
<P>     
     
<i>     
<center>     
Linda Chavez is president of the Center for Equal Opportunity.<br>     
<p>Contact <a href="mailto:lchavezusa@aol.com">Linda Chavez</a>.     
     
</i>     
     
</blockquote></blockquote>      
     
     
