<html>     
<head>     
<title>Chavez: Remember, It's The Deeds, Stupid  -- 5/29/96     
</title>     
</head>     
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">     
     
<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>     
<a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a><p><br>   
<i>   May 29, 1996</i><br>     
     
     
     
<h2> 
Remember, It's The Deeds, Stupid.
</h2>     
     
     
<a href="/townhall/columnists/chavez.html">     
Linda Chavez     
</a>     
<p>
BETHESDA, Md. -- Remember when there were two political parties in the 
U.S.? One party favored big government, the other wanted to cut it. 
One party talked about social justice, the other party demanded law 
and order. One party defended the right to do your own thing, the 
other encouraged traditional values. No more. At least when it comes 
to political rhetoric, the era of liberalism is over.
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
It's no accident that today's Democrats -- most notably Bill Clinton -
- sound a lot like staunch Republicans. The country has shifted to the 
right over the last four presidential elections and Democrats have had 
to move, too, at least rhetorically.
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
A recent Gallup poll shows Americans overwhelmingly support a 
conservative political agenda. Over 80% favor a balanced budget 
amendment, oppose racial preferences in schools and jobs, and endorse 
English as the official language. More than 70% support congressional 
term limits, sanction a constitutional amendment allowing school 
prayer and want to cut off welfare after two years unless recipients 
work. Similarly large majorities oppose legalizing homosexual 
marriages, favor school choice and want to ban partial-birth 
abortions.
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Given these numbers, no candidate in his or her right mind would 
publicly endorse deficit spending, racial quotas, or expanding 
welfare. When it comes to driving the political agenda Republicans win 
hands down -- which is why President Clinton is spending his time 
honing a conservative image.
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The same man who pushed gays in the military now says he'll happily 
sign federal legislation to ban gay marriages.
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The president who ignored welfare reform for his first two years in 
office, and then twice vetoed Republican welfare bills, now brags he's 
helped states to reform welfare on their own.
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The president who appointed dozens of federal judges with a history of 
allowing criminals back on the streets never misses a photo 
opportunity to surround himself with police officers who put those 
criminals behind bars in the first place.
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Clinton, ersatz conservative, hopes voters will forget his deeds and 
remember only his rhetoric. So far, the polls indicate his plan is 
working=2E Bill Clinton has never been so popular.
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Will this strategy carry him through the election? And will Clinton's 
latest tilt to the right convince Americans the Democratic Party 
represents the new conservatism? Not likely.
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Most voters haven't even begun to concentrate on the election in the 
fall. They're too busy planning their kids' graduations and family 
vacations to focus on November.
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
When voters do start to focus in earnest -- probably not until the 
party conventions -- Democrats will have a hard time sustaining their 
new-found conservatism. Public employees, who make up the biggest 
block of delegates, will hardly turn the Democrat convention into a 
cut-government-spending rally.
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The National Education Association won't countenance discussion of 
school choice. And Jesse Jackson would never permit his party to roll 
back racial preferences.
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Forget Democratic support for making English the official language. As 
for endorsing a balanced budget amendment to the Constitution, how 
would that make the 162 congressional Democrats who voted against it 
look?
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The fact is, Democrats can't make good on Republican issues even when 
it's in their interest to do so. When it comes to acting, not talking, 
1996 won't be any different. Come November voters will choose 
Republican action over Democratic words.
<BR>      
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;     
    
<P><P>     
<HR>     
<P>     
     
<i>     
<center>     
Linda Chavez is president of the Center for Equal Opportunity.<br>     
<p>Contact <a href="mailto:lchavezusa@aol.com">Linda Chavez</a>.     
     
</i>     
     
</blockquote></blockquote>      
     
     
<P> <br><center>     
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map">     
<img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0">     
</a></center>     
<P>     
</body>     
</html>
