<html>
<head>
<title>Crimson Tide and SDI</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center><i>May 30, 1995 </i>
<hr>

  

<h2>Crimson Tide and SDI
 </h2>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/dupont.html"><i>Pete du Pont</i> </a>
</center><hr>









 <P>
 






Crimson Tide is a sizzling movie, two hours of high tech, high tension 
confrontation wrapped around a post-Cold War terrorist scenario.  The 
film's tension is created by the need to fire a pre-emptive strike 
from a U. S. submarine in time to destroy rogue Russian missiles being 
fueled for an imminent launch.  But the real drama lies in the issues 
raised about America's security in the post-Cold War era.  
 
The film is fiction, so it doesn't bother to tell us that destruction 
on the launch pad is the only way to kill the Russian nukes.  But in 
the real world it's true:  once a missile is launched, the United 
States is unable to shoot it down.  We can pray for our family or 
friends who in a few minutes will be incinerated.  But we must suffer 
the missile's impact on Washington, Los Angeles, or wherever, because 
we have not built a missile defense system to protect us against 
incoming ICBMs. 
 <P>
We have the technology to build one.  A decade of Strategic Defense 
Initiative (SDI) research has developed the Patriot anti-missile 
missile, for example.  As we saw in the Middle East, the Patriot gives 
us the ability to protect small regions of civilians and soldiers from 
missile attack.  Further, our shipboard AEGIS missile system is a 
workable defender of our naval fleet. 
 <P>
What we lack is the will.  For years, the Congress has gutted funding 
for SDI research and national missile defense, until today's funding 
levels are less than one-third of a decade ago.  Now the Clinton 
administration is negotiating with the shadow of the former Soviet 
Union to be sure we never build a national missile defense. 
 <P>
So we sleep defenseless against a single terrorist missile.  Think for 
a moment about a rogue band of international terrorists operating in 
some remote corner of  Iran -- or Iraq, or in the mountains of North 
Korea, or in the Crimson Tide scenario in rebel Russia on the 
Kamchatka Peninsula.  How does the United States respond if such a 
group were to launch a missile towards our country?  We could, of 
course, retaliate and obliterate their nation, killing millions of 
innocent people.  But what do terrorists care about that?  How much of 
a deterrent would that be to a band of kamikaze extremists willing to 
destroy an American city? 
 <P>
Over a decade ago, when the idea of SDI was first proposed by the 
Reagan Administration, it was derided by liberals as a science fiction 
fantasy, an expensive and impractical dream.  Democratic Congresses 
and weak Presidents bought that argument, so today we have no missile 
defense. 
 <P>
Indeed, our nation has no better means of protecting its people today 
than it did back in the fifties and sixties, the days when American 
school children practiced hiding under their desks during air raid 
drills.  That is inexcusable.  The only reason there is not more of an 
outcry demanding construction of an anti-missile defense shield is 
because many people think it already exists.  In a survey conducted by 
the Coalition to Defend America, almost 60% of the respondents thought 
the "U.S. could destroy a ballistic missile" before it "could hit and 
do damage."  When the respondents were told no such capability exists, 
over 75% said they thought deployment of such a capability should be a 
priority for our nation. 
 <P>
It would not be an expensive priority.  A recent study conducted for 
the Heritage Foundation by former civilian and government military 
experts concluded that for just $2-3 billion over the next five years, 
our nation could adapt existing AEGIS technology to provide an 
effective missile defense for our nation. 
 <P>
As former President Ronald Reagan said in 1993, ten years after he 
launched our nation's SDI effort, "now more than ever, it is vital 
that the United States not back down from its efforts to develop and 
deploy strategic defenses.  It is technologically feasible, 
strategically necessary and morally imperative."  Frank Gaffney, Jr., 
the former Assistant Secretary of Defense in the Reagan Administration 
and currently head of The Center for Security Policy, notes the lack 
of such defenses is "our people's most serious strategic 
vulnerability." 
 <P>
For those who have not yet seen Crimson Tide, I won't give away the 
ending.  But, if  we ever do find a half-a-dozen ICBMs streaking 
towards America, we know our nation would be defenseless against them.  
That's a sad ending.  And Hollywood wouldn't even be around to film 
the sequel. 
 <P>


<i>The National Center for Policy Analysis is a public policy research 
institute founded in 1983 and internationally known for its studies on 
public policy issues.  The NCPA is headquartered in Dallas, Texas, 
with an office in Washington, D.C.</i>
<p>
[<a href="/townhall/columnists/welcome.html.cgi">Columnists</a>]
</html>

