<head>
<title>Washinton's New Math</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center><i>July 5, 1995 </i>
<hr>

  

<h2>Washington's New 
Math
 </h2>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/dupont.html"><i>Pete du Pont</i> </a>
</center><hr>
<p>







A decade ago as Governor of Delaware, I was trying to persuade the legislature to enact a bill granting lower tax rates to banks that moved business operations into our state.  Some liberal legislators objected to the tax incentive, arguing that the state would be taxing banks too little and the bankers would be making too much.<p> 
 "Look," I said, "today we get zero taxes from a bank that isn't here.  If one comes, we get the taxes and all the jobs it creates.  The banks will benefit and so will the state."<p>
 A similar argument currently rages in Washington about lowering capital gains tax rates.  Cut the tax rate, the liberals argue, and the government will tax too little and the wealthy will benefit too 
much.<p>
 Remember that capital gains - the increase in value of stocks or other assets - are only taxed if the asset is sold.  Obviously, affluent people have more assets than nonaffluent people.  But like the bank 
that isn't here, if they don't sell the asset, the government doesn't realize any tax revenue.  But if the prospective tax on the capital gain is lowered, some people who otherwise would have held onto their 
asset will decide to sell it.  The seller will reap his reward and capital gains tax revenue will increase.  So both the seller and the government will benefit.<p>
 Or so you might think.  But in the make-believe world of Washington arithmetic, the government will be scored as losing money.  The reason is that Washington's revenue estimators - the "scorekeepers" you read about - use what amounts to two sets of books.  On the one hand, they agree that the government will get a certain amount of additional revenue in the short run.  But the way they calculate the amount of gain would tax anyone's patience.  If someone doesn't sell an asset because they would have had to pay $10,000 in taxes, but does sell it when the tax is reduced to $7,000, the revenue estimators consider it a $3,000 revenue loss rather than a $7,000 revenue gain.  So a tax rate reduction that results in more dollars flowing to the Treasury is said to be a revenue loss - or, as the scorekeepers put it, a "tax benefit" to the seller.  Truth is indeed stranger than fiction. <p>
 Following this line of reasoning, if a retail store with goods that cost $500,000 and were priced at $1 million sold them for $750,000, the result would be not a $250,000 profit but a $250,000 loss.  And by 
Washington arithmetic, the sale would be unfair because it benefited the customers. <p>
 That's what the liberals argue in denouncing the tax cuts enacted by the House of Representatives - they are unfair because they benefit the wealthy.  As Bruce Bartlett, the former Treasury Department 
official who is now a Senior Fellow with the NCPA, has noted, things are not quite what they seem here.  The wealthy do hold more assets - or they wouldn't be wealthy - but 74% of the taxpayers who benefit from a capital gains tax cut have incomes of less than $75,000.  Indeed, when all the tax cut provisions of the House bill have taken effect, 65% of the benefits will go to taxpayers with incomes below $75,000, even though they pay only 49% of all federal taxes.  A bonanza for the wealthy?  Not exactly.<p>
Consider another example, the "draconian budget cuts" the liberals charge the Republicans are going to make in Medicare.  Under both the House and Senate versions of the budget, Medicare spending is 
scheduled to increase - by an average of 7% in each of the next five years. <p>
So how can an increase be a drastic cut?  By the same "Washington arithmetic" that makes tax revenue increases net losses to the Treasury.<p>
 Washington arithmetic uses a strange accounting system called "current services baseline budgets."  A current services baseline budget assumes that you will keep doing everything you do now exactly the same next year, and that in addition because of inflation and increased use of Medicare, next year's costs will rise as much as this year's.  That amount then becomes the "baseline" and any spending less than the baseline is a "cut" in the budget.  So a 7% increase in Medicare spending, compared to a 12% baseline budget, comes out as a 5% spending cut. What keeps all this from being hilarious is that the people who think this way have control of huge amounts of real money - our  money.  The truth is Washington arithmetic is designed to ensure that taxes are never cut and spending is never lowered. No wonder so much of the public lacks faith in the Congress.<p>
 Even the Delaware liberals who argued against the bank bill in the 1980s now admit it was a good thing.  Bank franchise taxes yielded $3 million in revenue the year before the bill was passed.  Last year, because a great many new businesses had moved to Delaware, revenues approached $100 million. <p>
Not bad.  Of course by Washington arithmetic, Delaware suffered a $97 million loss. <p>
 
<center>* * * *</center><p>
<i>The National Center for Policy Analysis is a public policy research Institute founded in 1983 and internationally known for its studies on public policy issues.  The NCPA is headquartered in Dallas,Texas, with an office in Washington, D.C.</i> <p>
<center>
