<html><HEAD><TITLE>Duplantier:   Dole on NAFTA -- 1/9/96</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<center><h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </h4><i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br><a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a> <br>January 9, 1996<br></i><hr><h2> Dole on NAFTA</h2></center><P> 
 [The efforts of Senator Bob Dole to distance himself from the North 
American Free Trade Agreement could signal a historic shift in U.S. trade 
policy.] 
 <P>
"The callous behavior of Bill Clinton and his trade allies in Congress in 
bulldozing the GATT and NAFTA treaties through in the face of the 
overwhelming opposition of the American people set the stage for the 
current counterrevolution on the trade front," says William Gill of the 
American Coalition for Competitive Trade. The seeds of that 
counterrevolution "were first sewn in 1990," says Gill, with publication 
of a book called Trade Wars Against America. That book persuaded Pat 
Buchanan and other conservative leaders that so-called free trade is "a 
destructive aberration that goes against the Constitution -- and the 
protectionist policy of George Washington and the other Founders -- the 
policy that built America." 
 <P>
Gill's group, the American Coalition for Competitive Trade, intends to 
keep publicizing the defects of free trade "until public opinion finally 
forces the government to repudiate this insane policy that is strangling 
America." As casualties of our country's self-defeating trade policy, Gill 
cites the nearly 80,000 mid-level managers to be laid off by AT&T, the 
12,000 bank employees made redundant by the pending merger of 
Chemical Bank and Chase Manhattan, the 1800 millworkers left stranded 
by the shutdown of Bethlehem Steel, and the 3200 textile workers let 
loose by Fruit of the Loom. 
 <P>
"Nowhere has the frenzy to cut jobs been more apparent than in the 
nation's once invincible defense industries," says Gill, noting that 
1,300,000 defense workers have lost their jobs since 1988, and 700,000 
more will be let go in the next two years. "Although most of these two 
million jobs will have disappeared because of cuts in the federal budget, a 
significant number can be traced to trade," says Gill. "Billions of dollars 
have been spent by the armed services on foreign products, many of them 
high-tech items invented in America and once made here before 
production was shipped overseas." As if that weren't bad enough, "it has 
become fashionable for U.S. defense companies to enter into joint 
ventures with foreign firms and governments in the production of some 
of our most sophisticated weaponry." Venture partners such as Japan 
have sold the technology acquired in this manner to our enemies. 
 <P>
Pat Buchanan has made protectionism the cornerstone of his bid for the 
Republican presidential nomination, and the-public's favorable response 
to that theme has not escaped the notice of front-running Republican 
presidential candidate Bob Dole. Last November, Dole expressed 
"significant disappointment" with the results of NAFTA, warned his 
colleagues in the Senate that America is "choking on new agreements," 
and called for a "cooling-off period" on trade pacts. "If Bob Dole sticks to 
his new guns on trade, and if he gets the Republican nomination in 1996, 
he will outflank Bill Clinton on an issue that now has most Americans up 
in arms against it," says Gill. 

<p>                           <P><i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i><p>
