<html><HEAD><TITLE>Duplantier:  Long-Term Commitment in Bosnia  -- 1/15/96</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a><center>
<h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </h4>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br><a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a> <br>January 15, 1996
<br></i><hr><h2>Long-Term Commitment in Bosnia </h2></center><P>

[Will American troops return from Bosnia in 12 months or less -- or will 
they still be there 20 years from now?] 
 <P>
John Hillen of the Heritage Foundation warns that "there are very serious 
questions that need to be answered about the political viability of the 
[Bosnian peace] accord and the effectiveness of the American military 
intervention to implement it." For starters, how realistic is a Bosnian state 
composed of "two separate political entities -- the Bosnian Muslim/Croat 
Federation and the Bosnian Serb Republic"? For such a state to be viable, 
says Hillen, "the two separate entities will have to show the most 
extraordinary goodwill and cooperation toward each other, qualities that 
have never been in evidence in Bosnia." Hillen contends that "the accord 
does not address fundamental issues of sovereignty and ethnic self-
determination. Instead, it freezes those unresolved issues in place and 
offers up an elaborate power-sharing agreement for a Bosnian central 
government." 
 <P>
The Bosnian Muslim/Croat Federation itself is pretty fragile. "There is 
considerable doubt about the solidarity of this alliance," says Hillen. 
Local support for the peace accord is also tenuous. "All three Bosnian 
Serbs present-at the- Dayton peace talks refused to sign the peace accord, 
and Bosnian Serb leaders denounced the accord within hours of its 
initialing." Among the issues left unsettled by the accord was the question 
of "how to integrate the two (or possibly three) rival armies into one that 
would serve the foreign policies of the central government." With such 
considerations in mind, Hillen concludes that "the United States will 
incur some form of continuing security obligation to Bosnia" far beyond 
its one-year commitment. 
 <P>
"There are also serious questions about the military feasibility of NATO's 
Implementation Force," says John Hillen of the Heritage Foundation. 
"Clearly defined, decisive, and attainable military objectives" have yet to 
be identified. The Bosnian peace implementation plan "strips any 
advantage from American ground forces and places U.S. troops in a 
passive and reactive posture." Despite President Clinton's assertions of a 
limited deployment, "the peace accord opens the door for NATO 
peacekeepers to perform many nation-building activities such as ensuring 
the free movement and resettlement of refugees, aiding humanitarian 
workers, resolving boundary disputes, creating secure conditions for free 
elections, and responding to violence against civilians." 
 <P>
The continuing expansion of peacekeeping duties -- and the perception 
that early withdrawal of U.S. troops could jeopardize the NATO mission 
-- would seem to dictate an extended American presence. "European 
allies have universally condemned President Clinton's proposed timetable 
for American forces in Bosnia," says John Hillen. "President Chirac of 
France has predicted an armed NATO presence that could last up to 20 
years." Clinton knows that the American public would never agree in 
advance to such "a protracted and costly intervention in an area of 
marginal strategic interest," but is counting on our reluctant support for 
his fait accompli. "Once the prestige, blood, and treasure of the United 
States are engaged," the Europeans hope that "the U.S. will have to see 
the intervention through to its conclusion." 
<p>                           <P>
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i><p>
