<html><HEAD><TITLE>Duplantier:  Media Violence and Our Kids -- 1/19/96</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a><center><h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </h4><i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br><a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a> <br>January 19, 1996<br></i><hr><h2>Media Violence and Our Kids</h2></center><P>  

["Industry executives claim there is no conclusive evidence  
demonstrating that video game violence affects young people." Recent  
research, however, show that claim is false.] 
 <P>
"In 1990, the National Coalition on Television Violence found that nine  
of 12 research studies on the impact of violent video games on children  
and adolescents reported harmful effects," says Jerry Melchisedeck of  
Focus on the Family. In a new report called Bringing Out the Worst in  
Us: The Frightening Truth About Violence, the Media, and Our Youth,  
Melchisedeck cites research identifying "a short-term relationship  
between playing violent games and increased aggressive behavior in  
younger children." Other research suggests that "the ill effects of video  
games are worse than those of TV because children actively control the  
violence rather than passively view it. In other words, the more children  
practice violent acts, the more likely they are to perform violent acts." 
 <P>
Jerry Melchisedeck says one researcher "reported that 40 out of 47 top  
video games he surveyed centered on violence, and 13 of those contained  
subthemes that emphasized the idea of women as victims." That same  
researcher "concluded that there are no gray areas in the behavior of  
game characters, and that players are rarely required to reflect or make  
contextual judgments." The manufacturers and distributors of violent  
video games resort to the usual dodge to justify their poisonous products.  
They insist they're only giving the customers what they want. "If  
consumer demand is the industry's guiding principle," says Melchisedeck,  
"then the future of video and computer gaming holds products that are  
progressively violent and realistically three-dimensional." 
 <P>
The demand for increasing levels of "realism," if you can call it that, has  
ominous implications. Video games now outsell Hollywood films, and  
that has movie moguls murmuring. Hollywood's getting in on the action,  
developing "interactive" movies that allow gamers gorged on two- 
dimensional gore to immerse themselves in cinematic savagery. 
 <P>
The ability to "download" video games is one of the major appeals of the  
so-called Information Superhighway. Thirty million people worldwide  
are now hooked up to the Internet, and video games aren't the only non- 
educational diversion available to them. Electronic mail is another. E- 
mail allows for the uncensored global transfer of words; sound; artistic,  
photographic, and videographic images; and computer software.  
Pornographers and pedophiles are already exploiting the perverse  
possibilities. 
 <P>
"Like the public library, the Internet provides access to volumes of up-to- 
date facts and data," says Jerry Melchisedeck. "Millions use it in the same  
manner as previous generations have referenced hardbound  
encyclopedias. For some, however, the Internet is a means of propagating  
their obscene, often violent, inclinations under the guise of First  
Amendment freedom. Access to this disturbing fare is as easy as a click  
of a button." Melchisedeck warns that "parents must not look to the  
government to protect their children. They must take an active role in  
monitoring the types of information" that the Internet delivers directly  
into their homes. 
 <p>                           <P><i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i><p>
