<html>
<head>
<title>Duplantier: Why America Must Cut Immigration -- 2/6/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>

February 6, 1996
<br></i>

<h2>Why America Must Cut Immigration </h2>
 


<P>
<blockquote><i>"Immigration has been, and can continue to be, in the national interest -- 
if properly regulated." </i></blockquote>
<P> 
The United States issues 675,000 immigrant visas a year. Senator Alan 
Simpson of Wyoming thinks that's far too many. As chairman of the Senate 
Subcommittee on Immigration, Simpson has proposed cutting the number to 
540,000, a 20 percent reduction. "The first and most important reason [for 
reducing immigration] is that the American people desire it," says Simpson. 
If Congress fails to take the initiative on this matter, he argues, "the 
people in the states and local communities of this country will most surely 
take it into their own hands to make the badly needed changes." 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The reason the American people want a reduction in immigration is "to allow 
the historically high flow of immigrants who have entered in the past 
several years to assimilate, to learn English . . . and to become 
integrated into the American economy." Simpson says that Americans "want 
criminal aliens swiftly expelled from this country. They want assurances 
that immigrants will not become a burden on the public welfare system. They 
want to know that American workers, particularly workers and students just 
entering the job market, will have a fair chance at the jobs offered by 
American employers -- and that wages of U.S. workers will not be undercut 
by foreign workers overjoyed to receive a fraction of what Americans earn." 
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
With regard to the immigration of family members, Simpson argues that 
"those opportunities should be reserved for the 'nuclear family' of 
citizens and permanent residents." He argues that "our present policy of 
giving preference to more distant family members . . . leads to the entry 
of in-laws of in-laws and persons who have only the most distant kinship 
relationship to the original immigrants -- or even none at all." 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
Senator Simpson believes that it is in the national interest to "restrict 
the immigration of unskilled workers, those who would directly compete with 
American workers entering the job market as a result of new limitations on 
the use of public assistance." He contends that "responsible immigration 
reform must also consider the more than one-third of a million Americans" 
who lost their jobs in the past year. "Of particular concern," he says, 
"are Americans who are laid off only to see their former jobs lawfully 
performed by temporary foreign workers.'" 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
Senator Alan Simpson's proposed legislation to revise immigration policy is 
based on the following common-sense principles: "Persons who are here 
illegally, particularly criminal aliens, should be quickly removed from the 
country through the reform of our detention and deportation process -- and 
while here should not be able to either work or obtain most forms of public 
assistance. Persons seeking to come legally should be swiftly united with 
their close family members in this country or . . . expeditiously and 
effectively screened so that they may take the jobs for which no qualified 
American is available. Finally, the overall number of immigrants should be 
reduced for at least five years." 
 
 
     




<P><P>

<P><i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i>

<P>
</blockquote></blockquote>




