<html>
<head>
<title>Duplantier: CRIME DECLINE -- 2/21/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<b>BEHIND THE HEADLINES</b><BR>


<i>
Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>
February 21, 1996<br><p></i>
<h2>Crime Decline</h2>


<i><blockquote>
It's an article of faith among liberals that prison sentences are no 
deterrent to criminal behavior, but statistics prove that would-be 
lawbreakers do consider the likelihood of punishment before resorting to 
crime.</blockquote></i>

<P>
Attorney Bruce Fein reports that "punishing and stigmatizing criminals 
is working. Violent crime is tumbling as prison populations swell, chain 
gangs are returning for serious offenders, three-time felons confront 
mandatory life sentences, juveniles are treated as adults for the 
commission of murderous crimes, shame is a growing feature of novel 
punishments, and parole is falling into disrepute."


<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
That's the good news, says Fein, in a recent Washington Times editorial. 
"The bad news is that the mass media and so-called penal experts are 
generally displaying fierce resistance to the good news." They don't want 
to relinquish their moral superiority. They can't bear to admit that the 
soft-hearted and fuzzy-headed policies they supported for so many years 
were monumental failures. They refuse to concede that common sense 
really does work. Fein says these superior beings are infatuated with 
rehabilitation programs and committed to fighting "the alleged 'root' 
causes of crime, i.e., poverty, unemployment, malparenting, ill 
education, and discrimination." Ideology keeps them from 
"acknowledging the obvious" and forces them to resort to 
"unconstructive whining" over get-tough policies.


<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Bruce Fein concedes that "violent crime remains intolerably high." But 
the recent decline is "a welcome relief" from the skyrocketing rates of the 
1960s and 1970s. "During those Great Society decades, treatment and 
rehabilitation were [misrepresented] as inexpensive and enlightened 
answers to crime, and criminal behavior was generally blamed on 
societal ills or psychiatric ailments." Fein contends that these misguided 
notions led to lighter sentences for convicted felons, and that such 
leniency served only to embolden the criminally inclined. Gradually, this 
sentimentalized view of the criminal as victim infected the general 
population, undermining the "cultural deterrence of crime" as manifested 
by "ostracism or community debasement of criminals for choosing evil." 
Fein says that such social penalties have a tremendous impact on crime 
and cites Japan as a nation where they continue to be used effectively.


<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
But stiff sentences and societal condemnation are making a comeback. 
"Unforgiving prison terms for felons work to reduce crime because an 
enormous proportion is attributable to recidivism," says Fein. Needless to 
say, repeat offenders commit no crimes while incarcerated. The longer 
they stay in prison, the fewer crimes they commit. Holding criminals 
responsible for their own behavior is back in style. Fading fast is the idea 
that criminals "deserved indulgence and sympathy because their 
depravity was engendered by societal wrongs or imperfections, or the 
happenstance of environmental factors."


<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Fein argues that the "community devastation wrought by such imbecility 
concentrated the minds of ordinary citizens, legislatures, and judges 
wonderfully. No longer are criminals viewed as victims of fate," he says, 
"but as evil creatures who have chosen to indulge their anti-social vices 
and passions; they should be shamed and disgraced."

<P><P>

<i>
Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit 
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free-
enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free 
transcript of this broadcast, send a self-addressed, stamped envelope to: 
America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105
</i>

</blockquote></blockquote>




