<head>

<title>Duplantier: Broadcasting for Freedom -- 03/06/96
</title>

</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES  </B><BR>
<i>Commentary From America's Future, Inc. <br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">
F.R. Duplantier</a><br>


March 6, 1996
</i><br>

<h2>
Broadcasting for Freedom
</h2>



<P>  <blockquote><i>

 
The Voice of America, Radio Free Europe, and Radio Liberty were  
instrumental in the collapse of Communism in Europe. So, why aren't we  
broadcasting the blessings of  liberty to the Communist countries of East  
Asia? 
 

</i></blockquote><P>


Lech Walensa and other veterans of the fight against Communist  
oppression in Eastern Europe have testified to the tremendous contribution  
that Radio Free Europe made to their struggle. Radio Free Europe's impact  
on the rise of the Solidarity union in Poland "cannot even be described,"  
said Walensa in a 1989 interview. "Would there be earth without the sun?"  
he asked rhetorically. 
 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

 
"Broadcasting can be one of the most effective and economical components  
of America's diplomatic and military efforts," says James Tyson, president  
of the Council for the Defense of Freedom. The $350 million currently  
allotted for the U.S. government's foreign broadcasting effort is a small  
fraction of the $250 billion annual defense budget. Ironically, the Voice of  
America, Radio Free Europe, and Radio Liberty were so effective in  
bringing the message of freedom to the captive nations of the world that  
many of our elected of officials have concluded that they are no longer  
necessary. "Following the collapse of communism in Europe, Radio Free  
Europe and Radio Liberty have been drastically downsized," says Tyson.  
The rush to cut back on such effective programs may prove to have been  
premature, especially if the resurgence of hardliners in Russia continues  
unchecked. "It is unfortunate," he says, "that Radio Liberty is becoming  
ineffective" just as Russia may be slipping back into dictatorship. 
 


<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;



Even if the situation in Russia does stabilize, there will still be 1.4 billion  
people suffering under brutal Communist governments in China, North  
Korea, Vietnam, Laos, and Cambodia. Tyson argues that our broadcasting  
efforts should be focused on the Far East. "China is the largest and most  
dangerous nation in the world today," he observes. "More than a million  
people are confined in its slave labor camps. With its massive increase in  
arms -- including long-range missiles and atomic, chemical, and biological  
weapons -- the regime represents a threat to all its neighbors." Tyson says  
recent emigres report a growing hunger among the common people in  
China for accurate news about what is really going on in their own  
country. 


<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;



 
A proposal to establish a Radio Free Asia broadcasting service was under  
consideration for several years, says Tyson, who served in 1992 on the  
Presidential Commission on Broadcasting to Asia. But it wasn't until 1995  
that Congress finally appropriated $10 million in start-up funds. Tyson  
contends that Radio Free Asia is "one of the most cost-effective policies we  
could follow," and estimates that an annual budget of $30 million would be  
sufficient to sustain the service. This would be money well spent. "If Radio  
Free Asia could accelerate the democratization of China as Radio Free  
Europe and Radio Liberty did in the Soviet bloc," says Tyson, "it would  
result in huge savings in our defense budget." 
<p> <p> <hr> 
<P>
<i>
 
Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit: it  
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free  
enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free  
transcript of this broadcast, send a self-addressed, stamped envelope to:  
America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105. 

</i>

