<head>

<title>Duplantier: Free Trade Follies -- 03/11/96
</title>

</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES  </B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.   <br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplatier
</a><br>


March 11,  1996
</i><br>

<h2>
Free Trade Follies
</h2>

<blockquote><i>
Did you think that the breakup of the Soviet Union and the liberation of the  
Captive Nations of Europe had tolled the death knell  for socialism? Well,  
one trade expert predicts that international treaties such as NAFTA and  
GATT will ultimately destroy the middle classes throughout the world and  
lead to a resurgence of the welfare state. 
 </blockquote></i>

<P>  

The World Trade Organization, created by the General Agreement on  
Tariffs and Trade, is now in operation. Its first major act was to order the  
United States to change its rules on the quality of imported gasoline or face  
sanctions by the international community. The governments of Venezuela  
and Brazil had appealed to the World Trade Organization to compel the  
U.S. to accept their gasoline, which does not meet U.S. environmental  
standards. Congress will now have to revise our Clean Air Act regulations  
regarding gasoline emissions or U.S. industries will face "cross-retaliation"  
trade sanctions. 
 


<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


This ruling is an omen of things to come, predicts William Gill of the  
American Coalition for Competitive Trade. Gill and his group were the  
first to warn that the North American Free Trade Agreement (known as  
NAFTA) and the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (known as  
GATT) "were the first big steps toward a world government that would rob  
America of our cherished independence as a nation." NAFTA and GATT  
threaten our prosperity as well as our sovereignty. Gill says nine million  
jobs "have been lost in the corporate downsizing" of the 1990s, one million  
of which are "directly attributable to NAFTA." 
 



<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


The damage doesn't end there. NAFTA "and other free trade efforts to  
erase all national borders" have unleashed an invasion of illegal drugs and  
illegal aliens into the United States. Infectious diseases are also entering  
our country at increasing rates. "The death rate from this invidious source  
rose . . .58 percent between 1980 and 1992," observes Gill, who describes  
this 12-year period as an "era when trade tore down virtually all the  
traditional defenses of our borders." 
 




<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;


Ironically, NAFTA has not done our neighbors south of the border any  
good either. Gill reports that "the middle class in Mexico is being wiped  
out, joining the hundreds of thousands of Mexican farmers driven off their  
land by NAFTA in the tragic trek downhill into abysmal poverty and  
despair." He warns that "free trade is sowing the seeds of revolution"  
throughout the world. "There have already been uprisings in Mexico and  
violent strikes in France," Gill observes, and this is only the beginning. He  
predicts that the unrest will rise, resulting in "a worldwide resurgence of  
socialism as the chaos caused by open borders forces governments into  
restoring and expanding welfare programs for the poor." The American  
Coalition for Competitive Trade intends to keep publicizing the defects of  
NAFTA and GATT and other free trade follies until public opinion finally  
forces our government to repudiate what William Gill calls an "insane  
policy that is strangling America." 
 



<P><P>
<HR>
<P>

<i>
Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit  
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our freeenterprise  
system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of  
this broadcast, send a self-addressed, stamped envelope to: America's  
Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105. 

</i></blockquote></blockquote>

<P> <br><center>
