<html><head>
<title>Duplantier: COST OF REGULATIONS -- 4/16/96</title></head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES  </B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.   <br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>
April 16, 1996
</i><br>
<h2>
COST OF REGULATIONS
</h2>

<P><blockquote><i>  
Federal regulations raise the cost of the goods and services we purchase 
by $400 billion annually. In other words, federal regulations cost the 
average American family $4, 000 per year!
</blockquote></i>


<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
"This year, OSHA will spend about $300 million and send out some 
2,000 inspectors across the country," reports John Hood of the Heritage 
Foundation. But those 2,000 snoops will inspect fewer than 10 percent of 
the six million workplaces in America, and are not likely to have any 
beneficial impact even at those locations. OSHA's workplace safety 
crusade "has been and will always be dwarfed by private-sector 
initiatives," says Hood. OSHA has "little value to add to the worker 
safety picture. But its costs -- measured in lower productivity and wages, 
as well as higher prices and taxes -- are significant."
<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Gary Becker of the Hoover Institution explains the impact of minimum 
wage hikes. "Higher labor costs reduce employment," he says. "A higher 
minimum will further reduce the employment opportunities of workers 
with few skills." In other words, teenagers, high school dropouts, and 
other low-skilled workers will lose their jobs if "their productivity is not 
high enough to justify the cost to employers." When workers lose their 
jobs, they stop paying taxes and start receiving unemployment or welfare 
benefits.
<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Richard Lesher of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce describes the 
Americans with Disabilities Act as "yet another weapon in the hands of 
disgruntled employees with personal axes to grind." Besides the cost of 
nuisance lawsuits, there is "the expense of retrofitting tens of thousands 
of workplaces and public facilities with wheelchair ramps, elevators, 
toilet stalls, and other special provisions to accommodate people with a 
wide variety of handicaps," says Lesher. "Together with the soaring cost 
of litigation, the Americans with Disabilities Act is proving to be a major 
expense for both public and private enterprises."
<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The U.S. Government banned the use of CFCs in aerosol spray cans in 
1978, and an international treaty phased out their use entirely in all 
industrial nations at the end of 1995. Jane Shaw and Richard Stroup of 
the Political Economy Research Center say these drastic actions are the 
result of hysteria, not scientific documentation. They argue that it's 
foolish for our federal government to prohibit the production of the 
nontoxic CFCs "used in millions of automobiles and refrigerators" when 
the available alternatives are "more costly, more corrosive to cooling 
systems, less dependable, and less manageable. Some even appear to be 
less safe." The benefits of halting CFC production are negligible, but the 
costs are likely to be extraordinarily high.
<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
"Just as our forefathers rebelled against 'taxation without representation,' 
today, private property owners are revolting over 'confiscation without 
compensation,'" says Congressman Billy Tauzin, author of the Private 
Property Owners Bill of Rights. "Clearly, the federal government has 
become our master rather than our servant," says Tauzin. "But American 
property owners . . . are fighting back."
<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
These are just a few examples of the regulatory abuses financed by our 
taxes.

<P><P>

<i>
Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit 
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free-
enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free 
transcript of this broadcast, send a self-addressed, stamped envelope to: 
America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.
</i>

</blockquote></blockquote>




