<html>
<head>
<title>Duplantier:  Environmental Phobias  -- 5/1/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>

May 1, 1996
<br></i>

<h2>Environmental Phobias</h2>
 


<P>
<blockquote><i>
What do radon, second-hand smoke, global warming, and the hole in the 
ozone layer all have in common? Just this: The danger they pose has 
been greatly exaggerated in order to justify some unnecessary 
government action.
</i></blockquote>


<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
"During 1995, scare stories about a future catastrophic greenhouse 
warming gained much momentum, while at the same time the evidence for 
such warming became weaker and weaker," observes Fred Singer of the 
Science and Environmental Policy Project in a recent Washington Times 
editorial. Those scare stories, unfortunately, provide seemingly 
justification for the Global Climate Treaty. The UN-sponsored 
Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change last year approved two 
summary reports that "convey the impression of impending doom and 
provide a spur for hasty and ill-advised action to cut the use of 
energy fuels." The reports created this misleading impression, says 
Singer, by "withholding crucial information (such as that the data 
show a warming rate of zero!)."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Singer points out that 1995 was also the year in which "the production 
of CFCs and other useful chemicals was banned -- in the mistaken 
belief that this policy would avert an epidemic of skin cancer. 
Scientific evidence does not support this hasty action," he says. 
"There is no data to indicate that ultraviolet radiation reaching the 
earth's surface is increasing by even a few percent -- as might be 
expected if the ozone layer were thinning."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
In November of last year, the Congressional Research Service released 
a report that reviewed published studies of the effects of "second-
hand" smoke. The report, says Singer, "found no support" for the 
Environmental Protection Agency's 1992 classification of second-hand 
smoke as a "Class A carcinogen" in the workplace. The risk of lung 
cancer posed by second-hand smoke was not statistically significant, 
it turns out, so the EPA simply redefined "statistical significance." 
Singer charges that the EPA "distorted science to establish a 
correlation and suggest a causation that cannot be proven with the 
data at hand."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Also in 1995, evidence was published demonstrating that low levels of 
radioactivity pose no health threat to humans. Ironically, says 
Singer, "the EPA is stirring up more fears just as we learn that 
naturally occurring radon is a very minor risk for lung cancer."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
So, is the earth getting warmer? No, but this is the excuse used to 
restrict access to energy. Is the ozone layer developing a hole? No, 
but this mythic menace sufficed to prohibit the production of CFCs. Is 
second-hand smoke a statistically significant carcinogen? No, but 
trumped-up findings to that effect could have led to mandated smoking 
bans in workplaces everywhere. Is radon the "number one environmental 
health hazard"? No, but EPA scare tactics will likely make radon 
mitigation a multi-billion-dollar industry. Fred Singer of the Science 
and Environmental Policy Project points out that "environmental 
regulation is now costing the nation more than $150 billion per year." 
That's a cost we can ill afford, especially for imaginary dangers.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
 <P>
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i>

<P>
</blockquote></blockquote>




