<head>
<title>Duplantier:  Education Reform  -- 5/10/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>

May 10, 1996
<br></i>

<h2>Education Reform</h2>
 


<P>
<blockquote><i>
During the recent government shutdown, the Department of Education 
determined that 89 percent of its workforce was "nonessential. " Why, 
then, are 4500 extra bureaucrats receiving $240 million a year in 
salaries?
</i></blockquote>



<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
"Principles of federalism embodied in the Constitution of the United 
States entrust authority over issues of educational policy to the 
States and the people, and a Federal Department of Education is 
inconsistent with such principles," claim the sponsors of the "Back to 
Basics Education Reform Act" now being considered by Congress. 
"Tradition and experience dictate that the governance and management 
of schools in the United States are best performed by parents, 
teachers, and communities. The intrusion by the Department of 
Education into education policy has not benefited the quality of 
education in this nation."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The reform bill's numerous sponsors claim that the Department of 
Education has "weakened the ability of parents to make essential 
decisions about their children's education and has undermined the 
capacity of communities to govern their schools. In the 15 years of 
its existence," they report, "the Department of Education has grown 
from 130 programs and a budget of $14 billion to over 240 separately 
authorized programs which cost almost $32 billion annually. Meanwhile, 
education performance has stagnated or deteriorated."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The reformers in Congress argue that the Department of Education has 
"fostered overregulation, standardization, bureaucratization, and 
litigation in United States education. The Department of Education 
spends large amounts of money on its own maintenance and overhead. As 
an organization, it is inefficient, ill-managed, and wasteful." What's 
the solution? "Only through initiatives led by parents and local 
communities with the power to act can the United States elevate 
educational performance toward an acceptable level. The Department of 
Education," the Congressmen observe, "has been hostile to many 
promising reform ideas."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The stated purpose of the Back to Basics Education Reform Act is four-
fold: "to improve the quality of elementary and secondary and higher 
education programs in the nation; to return the responsibility and 
authority for education to parents, teachers, communities, students, 
and States, and provide them greater control over education spending; 
to ensure that the Federal Government does not overregulate and 
interfere in the decision-making of parents, local communities, 
teachers, and students regarding education; and to ensure that 
Americans are able to compete in the global economy of the 21st 
century."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The Back to Basics Education Reform Act would repeal Goals 2000, the 
School-to-Work Opportunities Act, and the National Education 
Statistics Act. It would also abolish the Department of Education. In 
addition, the bill recommends "a review and evaluation as to the 
feasibility of further enhancing the ability of States and local 
communities to fund education by reducing the Federal tax burden and 
commensurately eliminating Federal Government involvement in providing 
grants for education programs." Isn't it time we put an end to Uncle 
Sam's unconstitutional meddling in education -- and give those 4500 
nonessential education bureaucrats a chance to do something productive 
with their lives?
<P>
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i>

<P>
</blockquote></blockquote>




<P> <br><center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map">
<img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0">
</a></center>
<P>
