<head>
<title>Duplantier: WELFARE REFORM/WA -- 5/31/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<b>BEHIND THE HEADLINES</b><BR>

<i>
Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>
May 31, 1996<br><p></i>
<h2> Welfare Reform/WA</h2>


<i><blockquote>
 

Demagogues may dismiss welfare reform as "discrimination against 
families, " but the truth is quite the opposite. </blockquote></i>
<P>
It isn't welfare reform that discriminates against families, but welfare 
itself, says John Carlson of the Washington Institute for Policy Studies in 
Seattle. "A young mother can receive a welfare check only if she doesn't 
marry the father, doesn't live at home, doesn't find a job, and doesn't save 
any money. You can't get much more anti-family than that," says 
Carlson. "Young men who father children out of wedlock don't have to 
take responsibility for their actions. The welfare system does it for them. 
And the mother isn't required to identify the father of the child. Again, 
you can't get much more anti-family than that."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

In the April issue of "Alternatives in Philanthropy," published by the 
Capital Research Center, Carlson argues that "we should apply the same 
kind of common sense to welfare reform that we would use if someone in 
our own family experienced trouble." A welfare reform bill now under 
consideration by the Washington State House of Representatives "would 
limit welfare benefits and include an additional period of reduced 
benefits for welfare recipients who are working. Recipients who don't 
look for work would have their benefits reduced. They could save money 
without being penalized, but cash benefits would not be increased for 
recipients who have more children."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

In the same issue of "Alternatives in Philanthropy," Lynn Harsh and Bob 
Williams of the Evergreen Freedom Foundation in Olympia, Washington 
agree that the welfare reform proposed in the State House "moves in the 
right direction." It provides for "a maximum of 36 months on 
assistance," requiring recipients to "sign contracts outlining their 
responsibilities" and to "participate in a job-training and job-search 
program." The legislation would require unwed mothers to identify "the 
fathers of their children," while denying cash payments to unmarried 
mothers who are minors. Harsh and Williams recommend that the 
reforms also include stringent enforcement of child support laws, the 
easing of restrictions on adoption, "greater tax incentives for charitable 
contributions," and the changing of program incentives "so that state 
welfare agencies redefine success as the number of people removed from 
welfare rolls and placed in long-term employment." The two policy 
analysts note that "the mere talk of tough welfare reform seems to be 
having an effect. Fewer people are applying for welfare in Washington 
State than last year despite no significant changes in the law or the 
economy."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

Why not support what works? "Hundreds of charities, nonprofit 
organizations, and private-sector job-training and placement programs 
already serve the needy," observe Harsh and Williams. "Many of them 
have a proven record of operating efficiently and with a high degree of 
accountability. In the long run we advocate abolishing government-run 
welfare entirely. Far from being a cruel or reckless approach, this change 
would help renew our families, neighborhoods, churches, and 
communities -- the institutions best able to serve the needy."
<P><P>

<i>
Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit 
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free-
enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free 
transcript of this broadcast, send a self-addressed, stamped envelope to: 
America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105
</i>

</blockquote></blockquote>

