<html>
<head>
<title>Duplantier: THE REAL McCARTHY-- 6/05/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif">
</a><b>BEHIND THE HEADLINES</b><BR>

<i>
Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>


<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>
June 5, 1996<br><p></i>
<h2> The Real McCarthy</h2>


<i><blockquote>



What exactly did Senator Joseph McCarthy do to provoke such a storm 
of protest in the early 1950s? Just his job, that's all!
</blockquote></i>
<P>
As chairman of the Senate Committee on Government Operations, 
Senator Joseph McCarthy was responsible for "watching this vast 
bureaucracy -- to spot graft, incompetence, extravagance, and disloyalty. 
As chairman of this committee [McCarthy was] merely carrying out his 
mandate in searching for cases of disloyalty inside the government." 
McCarthy did not wage his "war on communism any place but inside the 
government of the United States," asserted John T. Flynn in a nationally 
syndicated radio broadcast in 1954.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

Of the slightly more than 200 witnesses who were examined publicly by 
the committee, more than a third refused to answer, most of whom 
invoked the Fifth Amendment. Flynn reminded his listeners that "almost 
all of these were government workers at various level of importance -- 
and in bureaus or agencies peculiarly subject to secrecy. The evil 
McCarthy [was] shooting at [was] treason. The people he [was] stalking 
[were] traitors -- most of them dedicated to the interest of our deadliest 
enemy at home and in the world, Communist Russia."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

In addition to exposing the communist conspirators at the Institute of 
Pacific Relations (who had betrayed China and most of Asia to the 
Russians), McCarthy also uncovered agents in the Government Printing 
Office. "A great number of highly secret documents are printed in the 
Government Printing Office," Flynn observed. "The Senator found there 
persons with impressive records of Communist activity. The FBI had 
reported these persons repeatedly but nothing was done about it." Flynn 
noted that, as a result of McCarthy's investigations, "the entire security 
panel in the department was removed and all the security regulations 
overhauled. The penalty [for stealing secret documents] was changed 
from a few days suspension to dismissal." McCarthy's Committee also 
"conducted investigations at Fort Monmouth, New Jersey, where highly 
secret radar equipment [was] developed. This resulted in the suspension 
of 33 security risks from this very sensitive U.S. Army spot."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

The recently released Venona documents confirm what Flynn concluded 
in his 1954 broadcast: that "the most important objective of the 
Communist conspiracy has been to get Communists or Communist dupes 
inside our government departments. Their aim [was] to keep Russia 
advised of what the American government [was] doing and, even more 
important, to actually take part in shaping the decisions on policy of our 
government. The decisions to abandon Czechoslovakia, Poland, 
Hungary, Yugoslavia, Eastern Germany, and a part of Austria to Russia 
as World War II ended were all accomplished by Communists and pro-
Reds in our State Department."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;

Infiltration of our government was "the most important enterprise of the 
Communist conspiracy in America," said John T. Flynn. "It has cost 
millions of dollars, the lives of numerous men, and incredible labor and 
patience on the part of the Communist leaders." Flynn insisted that 
"McCarthy was not persecuting radicals or even Communists. His aim 
was only at Communists and spies inside the American government."

<P><P>

<i>
