<html><head>
<title>Any U.N. Treaty is a Treaty We Can Do Without -- Duplantier</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center><h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </h4>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>
<> href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a> <br>
 October 24, 1995 <br></i>
<hr>
<h2>Any U.N. Treaty is a Treaty We Can Do Without</h2></center>
<P>

 
Any United Nations treaty is a treaty we can do without, because it will  
surely threaten the rights of Americans . 
 <P>
One of Douglas MacArthur's famous lines was, "Old soldiers never die,  
they just fade away." Unfortunately, old treaties not only never die; they  
don't even fade away. Old treaties retain their life forever. Also,  
unfortunately, the United Nations has some old treaties lying around, and  
we must be ever-vigilant if we are to be sure they are never ratified. 
             <P>
The International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights would change  
the marriage laws of most of our states in the name of equality and  
thereby repeal the fundamental legal rights possessed by American wives.  
This Treaty would give carte blanche to some future international  
tribunal by insisting that all persons are "entitled without discrimination  
to equal protection of the law," without defining what that means. The  
Treaty would allow any foreign government, friendly or unfriendly. to  
accuse the United States of violation. It wouldn't take very long for the  
envious nations of the world to begin their feeding frenzy. How much  
sympathy do you think we would receive from a UN human rights  
committee stacked against us? 
                       <P>
The International Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Racial  
Discrimination would require the United States to "prohibit and bring to  
an end, by all appropriate means, including legislation as required by  
circumstances, racial discrimination by any persons, group or  
organization." This provision would override our First Amendment right  
to freedom of association in private clubs and other private action. A UN  
Committee would hear complaints against us, without revealing the  
identities of the complainants. The Treaty's enormously broad  
descriptions of racial discrimination would offer endless opportunities for  
mischief as the Committee demands explanations and remedies for our  
alleged transgressions. 
                              <P>
The International Covenant on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights  
would require the United States to "recognize the right of everyone [in  
the world] to an adequate standard of living for himself and his family,  
including adequate food, clothing and housing, and to the continuous  
improvement of living conditions." It would further require that we  
"ensure an equitable distribution of world food supplies in relation to  
need." How would we recognize that "right," and how would we ensure  
that "equitable distribution"? With an ever-increasing transfer of 
American wealth, that's how! 
                                        <P>
The worst aspect of the UN Treaty on Economic, Social and Cultural  
Rights is its refusal to include the fundamental right to own property.  
This is why the Truman, Eisenhower, Kennedy, Johnson, Nixon. and  
Ford Administrations consistently took the position that the United States  
would not sign it. President Jimmy Carter reversed this position and  
signed it, which means this UN treaty is sitting around in the bottom  
drawer waiting for a chance to be ratified. 
                 <P>
All these UN treaties are bad news for the United States, and a threat to  
our constitutional liberties. If you hear that any UN treaty is being  
considered in the U.S. Senate, be sure to tell your Senator to vote no. 
 <p>           <P>
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i><p><br><br>
