<html><head><title>Duplantier:  CLINTONS CIVIL SERVICE REFORM FLAWED</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a><center><h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </h4><i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br><a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a> <br>November 20, 1995<br></i><hr><h2>Clinton's Civil Service Reform Flawed</h2></center><P>



             

President Clinton has made much of his plan to "reinvent government, " 
but a prominent management consultant says the President's proposed 
reforms would only make matters worse.
<p>
President Clinton promised to overhaul the federal civil service so as "to 
make the entire federal government both less expensive and more 
efficient, and to change the culture of our national bureaucracy awav 
from complacency and entitlement toward initiative and empowerment." 
But Donald J. Devine. former director of the U.S. Office of Personnel 
Management says that "this reinvention will weaken management. Iead 
to greater inefficiencies. dilute individual performance initiative. 
reinforce the culture of complacency. and make government less 
accountable."
<p>
In a Heritage Foundation report entitled "Making Government Work," 
Device argues that the President's proposed reforms downplay the 
importance of individual merit and performance and shift control over 
the executive branch from the President to federal bureaucrats and 
unions. "Instead of reinventing government." savs Devine, "Clinton's 
proposals would make things worse by transferring leadership to 
committees and unions and assuring weak executive leadership."
<p>
President Clinton's proposals ignore the key principles of "real 
government reform." says Devine. the first of which is to "keep the 
mission simple." To be successful. every government agency must have 
"a simple. clear mission with an imaginative leadership dedicated to that 
mission." Unfortunately. "government missions have become enormously 
more complex" than they used to be. and civil servants are now saddled 
with responsibilities that are ill-defined or contradictory. "Government." 
Devine insists. "can work effectively only when relatively few things are 
assigned unambiguously to a few institutions with sufficient esprit le 
corps to do them well."
<p>
Devine notes that our central government has "strayed far from its 
federalist roots" and recommends that its scope be strictly limited once 
again. "Functions properly performed by the states should be transferred 
back to them." he says. The federal government should also take 
advantage of the "reduced costs. greater efficiency, and improved 
management that flow from contracting work out to the private sector."
<p>
Devine calls for the reestablishment of "a true merit system." The hiring 
and promotion of civil servants must be based on "knowledge, skills, and 
abilities" once again. he says. The President and his department heads 
must accept and assert their responsibility for the activities of the 
executive branch. Devine notes that "the thrust of the Clinton reforms is 
to remove authority from the political and career executives . . . and 
transfer it to labor-management councils." This is foolish and 
irresponsible. says Devine. "Without political leadership. when the 
President gives an order, there is no reason to assume anything will 
happen down the line in the federal bureaucracy. That is why 
responsibility in current law rests with the political agency head." 
Devine argues that "effective government management requires strong 
agency leadership," which in turn requires straightforward missions and 
clear-cut performance standards.

<p>                           <P><i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i><p><br><br><center><br><a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a></center></body></html>
