                         <html><HEAD><TITLE>Duplantier:  PUBLIC SCHOOLS ARE A DISMAL FAILURE</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a><center><h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </h4><i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br><a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a> <br>November 28, 1995<br></i><hr><h2>Public Schools are a Dismal Failure</h2></center><P>
[It's time to face up to the failure of our nation's educational system. A 
Nobel Prize-winning economist argues that the only way to save the 
public schools is to privatize them.]
<p>
"Our elementary and secondary educational system needs to be radically 
reconstructed," says Nobel economist Milton Friedman of the Hoover 
Institution. The system is hopelessly defective, and the "technological 
and political revolutions of the past few decades" are only going to make 
it worse. Friedman predicts that "a widening gap between the incomes of 
the highly skilled . . . and the unskilled" will lead to "serious social 
conflict. "
<p>
Friedman points out that dramatic technological advances have "made it 
possible for a company located anywhere in the world to use resources 
located anywhere in the world, to produce a product anywhere in the 
world, to be sold anywhere in the world." Equally dramatic political 
changes in Eastern Europe and Latin America have led to the widespread 
rejection of central planning in favor of free markets and "added greatly 
to the pool of low-wage, yet not necessarily unskilled labor" with which 
U.S. workers must compete. These developments have put "downward 
pressure on the wages of low-skilled labor," widening the income gap in 
America. If this gap continues to widen, "it threatens to create within our 
own country a social problem of major proportions," warns Friedman. 
<p>"Such stratification is a recipe for social disaster." Only a dramatically 
improved school system can brighten the prospects of Americans at the 
bottom of the economic ladder.
<p>
Friedman argues that "radical reconstruction can be achieved only by 
privatizing a major segment of the educational system." To encourage "a 
gradual yet substantial transfer from government to private enterprise." 
<p>Friedman recommends "a voucher system that enables parents to choose 
freely the schools their children attend." He concedes, however, that "the 
political power of the school establishment" has been, and will continue 
to be, a major obstacle to this effort.
<p>
Central city residents suffer most from the poor quality of public 
schooling. "The reason is partly the deterioration of our central cities, 
partly the increased centralization of public schools." says Friedman. 
<p>"Power has moved from the local community to the school district to the 
state, and to the federal government. About 90 percent of our kids now go 
to so-called public schools. which are really not public at all but simply 
private fiefs primarily of the administrators and the union officials."
<p>
Friedman insists that everyone will benefit from a voucher system, 
"except a small group of vested interests." The big winners will be "the 
residents of central cities, who will have a real alternative to the wretched 
schools so many of their children are now forced to attend." That "small 
group of vested interests" has tremendous clout, however. <p>"The teachers' 
unions are bitterly opposed to any reform that lessens their own power," 
says Friedman, "and they have acquired enormous political and financial 
strength." They won't hesitate to use that strength to defeat "any attempt 
to adopt a voucher system."
<p>                           <P><i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i><p><br><br><center><br><a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a></center></body></html>
