<html><HEAD><TITLE>Duplantier:  ANTI-RELIGIOUS BIGOTRY RAMPANT IN HOLLYWOOD</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a><center><h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </h4><i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br><a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a> <br>December 4, 1995<br></i><hr><h2>Anti-religious Bigotry Rampant in Hollywood</h2></center><P>
[A new documentary offers numerous examples of the anti-religious 
bigotry that is rampant in Hollywood.] 
 <p>
"For years now, the entertainment industry has attacked our faith and 
undermined our value system," observes Dr. James Dobson of Focus on 
the Family, in his introduction to a new documentary entitled Hollywood 
vs. Religion. "The entire Judeo-Christian tradition is ridiculed." The 
hour-long video tape is narrated by Michael Medved, New York Post 
film critic and co-host of the PBS program called Sneak Previews.  He 
examines more than 50 contemporary films that lampoon the religious 
beliefs of the American people. Unfortunately, this is just a sampling.  <p>
"There are a great many other movies that also mock our faith," says 
Dobson. 
 <p>
According to Medved, Hollywood's hostility toward religion is a fairly 
recent development. Showing heartwarming scenes of Spencer Tracy in 
Boys Town, Bing Crosby in The Bells of St. Mary's, and Julie Andrews 
in The Sound of Music.  Medved notes that "this tradition of taking a 
positive view of the clergy and the faithful continued well into the l960s." <p>
But the film world has lost its fondness for the faith.  "Today, by contrast, 
moviemakers will stretch to insert images of vicious clergymen or crazed 
killer Christians,'' says Medved.  They'll even go so far as to introduce 
vicious stereotypes into remakes of old films -- such as The Blob and 
Cape Fear -- where none existed before. 
 <p>
What are the stereotypes? Here's how Hollywood views the world of 
religion: "The Catholic Church is linked to the Mafia. Evangelical 
believers are suckers and dupes. In their hearts, many Christians want to 
take over the country and establish a dictatorship. Orthodox Jews are 
hypocrites.  Agnostics, on the other hand, are wise, wonderful people." <p>
Hollywood will bend over backwards not to offend the fringe elements of 
society, but the cherished beliefs of the vast majority of Americans are 
fair game. "Only the sensibilities of mainstream Western religious groups 
are repeatedly ignored." says Medved. "And many films send the 
unmistakable message that higher truth can only be found outside the 
teaching of all organized faith." 
 <p>
Everything in Hollywood is carefully calculated, says Medved, and that 
includes the anti-religious imagery that we are seeing more and more of: 
"It's no accident when filmmakers show us so many villains who happen 
to be religious," he observes.  Why do they do it?  Directors and 
producers like to claim that they're only giving the public what it wants, 
but the box-office failure of such offensive movies as The Last 
Temptation of Christ puts the lie to this claim. More than three dozen 
films featuring repugnant religious stereotypes have come out of 
Hollywood in recent years. "Almost all of these movies ended up losing 
money," says Medved. The real reason that such films continue to be 
made is that they reflect the mindset of a "tightly knit community whose 
members happen to share some similar, unspoken values and biases. And 
one of those biases involves sincere and deep-seated contempt for 
organized religion." 
 <p>                           <P><i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i><p><br><br><center><br><a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a></center></body></html>
