<head>
<title>Remembering V-J Day</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<hr>
<center><h2>Remembering V-J Day</center></h2>
<p>
<center>By<br><a href="/townhall/columnists/howley.html"> Kathleen Howley</a></center> 
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<p>
In all the controversy surrounding the 50th anniversary of the 
dropping of the atomic bomb on the weapons factories of Hiroshima and 
Nagasaki, there's been a bit of the human element that has been lost 
on one side of the debate.
<p>
No, I'm not talking about the fate of the 195,000 people who were 
killed or injured in those congested cities. Their tragic story has 
been told, as well it should. 
<p>
The world has not forgotten them.
<p>
But, what about the fate of the U.S. forces poised off the coast 
of Japan, ready to launch an invasion that was certain to produce the 
heaviest casualties of World War II?
<p>
It's easy, 50 years later, to disagree about projected fatality 
figures. Would there have been 80,000 American losses during the inch-
by-inch fighting for Japanese soil, or 180,000, or 300,000, or more? 
In recent weeks, the guests on the Sunday morning talk show seem to 
preen themselves as they dispassionately debate the issue. 
<p>
But, meanwhile, the men who were on those ships, and their 
families, have a different view of history. It's a more gripping sense 
of what might have been.
<p>
I know, because my father, Michael J. Howley, was part of that 
invasion force. He was, then, a somewhat-scrawny, 18-year-old Radarman 
First Class on the U.S.S. Akutan, an ammunition ship that was 
responsible for re-supplying the front-line battleships with shells 
and bullets. 
<p>
In the brutal, island-hopping campaigns that brought the U.S. 
forces to the shores of Japan, the Navy's job was to launch massive 
bombardments before each landing in an attempt to pave the way for the 
Marines. At the same time, the ships had to defend themselves against 
enemy fighter pilots and suicidal kamikaze attacks.
<p>
Dad enlisted in the Navy when he was 17, fresh out of Boston 
College High School. At first, his parents objected, saying he was too 
young. But, in the end, they signed the document required for under-
aged recruits, and sent their son to fight for their adopted country.
<p>
By August of 1945, he was a veteran of the Liberation of the 
Philippines, and, a more searing memory, the Battle of Okinawa, where 
the U.S. Navy experienced some of the heaviest losses of the war. 
<p>
He never had to worry about being crippled or maimed. All it took 
to incinerate an ammo ship was one well-placed bullet, or one 
successful kamikaze plane. 
<p>
In fact, in the final months of war, the U.S.S. Mt. Hood, also an 
"AE," or ammunition supplier, went down with all hands lost, with the 
exception of an officer and a squad of sailors who were on a nearby 
island. The explosion of the ship's 8,800 tons of bombs blew a 300-
foot-long crater in the ocean floor.
<p>
To acknowledge the awesome destructive power contained within the 
hulls of the AEs, the Navy named all of them, in the World War II 
years, after volcanoes.
<p>
When we were young, the only specifics Dad ever told us about the 
war were the funny stories, like the time he was on shore patrol and 
was ordered to arrest a group of sailors, who turned out to be his 
shipmates.
<p>
And, there was also the amusing detail about the "little white 
lie" he told his mother, who was home in Boston praying unending 
Rosaries for her two sons in uniform -- one, my uncle, in the Army, 
and, the other, my Dad.
<p>
"Mamie," an Irish name for "mother," spent the war years believing 
my father was on a low-level supply ship in the backwaters of the 
Pacific. To support this subterfuge, he filled his letters with 
imaginary details of how many blankets they had transported, and how 
bored he was.
<p>
"I didn't want her to worry more than she already did," he 
explained. 
<p>
Every year, at the anniversary of the bombings of Nagasaki and 
Hiroshima, the media focuses on one angle: the plight of the citizens 
of those two cities.
<p>
But the historical context, the backdrop for the decision to drop 
the bomb, seems to have been lost. 
<p>
There has been little mention of the fact that the Japanese were 
working on their own A-bomb, or that they had a habit of placing 
armament factories in residential areas, or that the citizens of 
Hiroshima and Nagasaki were warned by U.S. leaflet drops to flee their 
homes, or that our prisoners of war were starving to death as they 
waited for liberation.
<p>
Most of all, we seem to have forgotten the plight of the thousands 
of soldiers and sailors -- many of them teenagers -- who waited 
onboard the ships of the American invasion fleet.
<p>
Whether you believe the lowball figures put forth by today's 
revisionists, or the higher figures accepted as fact in 1945, the 
bottom line is: vast numbers of those young men would not have 
survived the Battle of Japan.
<p>
They would have have missed their chance to live their lives, to 
have families, and to grow old.
<p>
Surely, their stories deserve some mention.
<p>
<i>Kathleen Howley is a syndicated columnist<br>
Copyright 1995, Living Word Syndicate
<p>
Internet:73360.271@compuserve.com</i>
<p>
