<html>
<head>
<title>You must learn to forgive</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<hr>
<center><h2>You Must Learn To Forgive You</h2><p>
 By<br><a href="/townhall/columnists/howley.html"> Kathleen Howley</a>
</center><hr><p> 
 

Only in this day and age could a magazine devote an entire, 2,600-word 
article to the subject of confession, and not once mention the word 
"God." <p>

Cosmopolitan did it, in their August issue. The gist of the story was: 
the highest aim in life is to obtain self-forgiveness. <p>

That's right. YOU must learn to forgive YOU. Confess your sins to 
yourself, or to a pal. No need to submit yourself to divine authority. 
Learn how to erase your guilt. Just get rid of it.  <p>

Silly you for feeling guilty in the first place.<p>  

Don't change your habits. Don't even consider the possibility that 
there is such a thing as absolute, immutable truth, or that some 
actions are intrinsically wrong -- or that feelings of actual guilt, 
as opposed to imagined or neurotic guilt, exist for a good reason. <p>

Don't ponder the idea that Hell could, indeed, be real, whether you 
believe in it or not. <p>

Just get to a good therapist, and work through your feelings.<p> 

I suppose that's a much easier route than asking for God's 
forgiveness, which requires an acknowledgment of His authority, true 
repentance, and an earnest resolution to try to sin no more. <p>

That would be life-changing. Earthshaking, in fact.  <p>

I'd wager a guess that the average Cosmo subscriber is nowhere near 
taking that first step. But, without God's absolution, they're just 
changing seats on the Titanic.<p> 

Forgiving yourself may, in fact, give temporary relief. But, until God 
forgives you, your deeds will always exist, if only in the deepest 
recesses of your mind, and, certainly, in your soul. <p>

Without His supernatural grace, dispensed through the Sacrament of 
Penance, they can never be cast "as far as the east is from the west." <p>

Sin, or "guilt," as Cosmo phrased it, "can torment you, make you sick 
-- even weaken your body's immune system." <p>

The article, titled "Are Guilty Secrets Haunting Your Life?" goes on: 
"People often become immobilized, whether they know it or not, unable 
to get on with their lives until they tell the truth." <p>

Ahh, is that all it takes? Having an honest chat with a friend, or 
spending $100 an hour for a therapist? Following Cosmo's logic, 
America should be the healthiest, happiest county in the world.  <p>

After all, is there any self-help route we haven't tried? Is there a 
new therapy technique we've passed up? <p>

Have we left anything unsaid? Is there any topic -- any? -- that 
hasn't been discussed in full detail on Oprah or other TV shows? <p>

And yet, America seems, on the whole, to be much more depressed, 
guilt-ridden, and lonely -- compared to, say, a time when we were a 
God-fearing country.<p> 

No. There's a lot more to healing the deadly effects of sin than just 
telling someone about it.<p>  

There's nothing wrong with therapy, or talking with friends. But 
neither will set us free.<p> 

Perhaps an easier way to explain this complex theological fact is with 
a simple story.<p>  

A man, troubled by his failings, confessed his sins to a Catholic 
priest, and received Sacramental absolution. Later, he spent time in 
prayer with God, and brought up the subject of his already-confessed 
sins.<p>  

The answer from God -- who, although all-knowing, may have been trying 
to make a point -- was, "I don't remember."<p> 

And, this gentle reminder was enough to give the penitent the feeling 
of elation that comes with true freedom. <p> 

I've felt that feeling too, as I've left a confessional. <p>

As Jesus told the Apostles: "Whose sins you shall forgive, they are 
forgiven them; and whose sins you shall retain, they are retained." 
(John 20:23) <p>

About six years ago, after I converted from being an atheist and a 
lapsed Catholic, I spent some time with a college friend who was not a 
believer.<p> 

She was quick to say that I seemed much happier since re-embracing the 
faith. But, she also said that she could never go back to being a 
Catholic because she couldn't stand living with "all that guilt." <p>

"Do I seem guilt-ridden?" I asked her. <p>

"No," she said.<p> 

"That's because the whole point is that Jesus died for our sins, in 
place of us. So, we get off scot-free. No guilt. All I have to do is 
try to live as He wants, and when I fail, I go to Confession, ask for 
His forgiveness, and I leave with a clean slate," I said.<p> 

"A clean slate..." she said, thoughtfully. "That sounds kinda nice." <p>


 
Copyright 1995, Kathleen Howley <br>
 Internet:73360.271@compuserve.com<p>
