<html>
<head>
<title>Rockwell: Beltway Bandits All -- 8/1/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<I>  
August 1, 1996 
</I>


<h2>
Beltway Bandits All
</h2>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/rockwell.html">
 Llewellyn H. Rockwell, Jr.
</a>

<P>

  <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Conservative pundits are having the time of their lives 
blasting Bob Dole, with several calling on him to drop out before 
the convention. The stated reason: his lifetime of politicking 
and state-building has put him hopelessly out of touch with the 
public's desire for real change in Washington. If he becomes the 
nominee, they say, Republicans will lose. 
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Perhaps so. At the same time, it's not fair to single out 
Mr. Dole for such scrutiny, while the leaders of the current 
Congress get off scot-free. After all, Newt Gingrich, Richard 
Armey, and Trent Lott are as much creatures of Washington as Mr. 
Dole. Their reluctance to upset the system that created them and 
sustains their power is what dashed the early hopes that this 
Congress would do something extraordinary. 
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Sensing that the public has not been impressed, the 
Republican leadership is at last getting defensive about its 
record. Mr. Armey, the House Majority Leader, was particularly 
incensed when a news story from the <i>New York Times</i> suggested, 
without further elaboration, that this Congress "has not 
accomplished much else despite its grand early promises" other
than welfare reform.  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
While hardly anyone would dispute this (even if the welfare 
reform looks piddling), Mr. Armey has taken grave offense. In 
thinking this way, he says, we are ignoring "the truth about the 
accomplishments of this Congress." He proceeds with a strange 
list of items that merely remind us of the extent that this 
Congress has indeed squandered the opportunity of a century. 
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Mr. Armey says "we achieved more than $53 billion in 
discretionary savings." But this is only an "accomplishment" if 
you keep track of the new additions to Congress's Dictionary of 
Budgetary Wordplay. The term "savings" here does not mean cuts, 
which Congress promised, or even cuts in the normal rate of 
increase. It refers to the difference between two artificial 
forecasts that Congress itself controls. 
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
You can try this technique at home. List all the purchases 
you have made this month, no matter how frivolous or how much you 
had to borrow to make them. Measure that against how much you 
would spend if you had  really  splurged. The difference between 
the two is how much you "saved" last month. This budgetary device 
can make your savings rate skyrocket--at least in your own mind. 
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The term "savings" is smoke and mirrors, while the official 
record will show that this Congress increased total government 
spending at the usual rate. The Congressional leadership has 
accepted and reinforced the Washington rule that spending must 
always increase at the rate of inflation, plus the rate of 
growth, for a total of 5 to 6 percent per year.
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Sensing that some people may be on to this game, Mr. Armey 
turns to a page in the Art of Political Dissembling. He says 
Congress has balanced, by the year 2002, that "part of the budget 
that Congress controls." Let's say a three-pack-a-day smoker 
tries the same trick. If he announces "I have quit smoking by 
2002, at least the part I control," do you believe him?
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
When Ronald Reagan was president, Republicans heaped scorn 
on the Democratic Congress when it claimed that it only 
controlled a portion of the budget. Now the Republican Congress 
uses the same implausible defense of its profligacy. If the 
Congress doesn't control the purse strings, who does?  
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
While claiming not to control the budget, the Congressional 
leadership is also trying to evade other responsibilities. It 
passed an unconstitutional "line-item veto" which not only 
tramples on the separation of powers, but also vastly enhances
the political power of the next president, who will likely be 
Congress's supposed opponent. 
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
In other ways, Congress has stepped up government power, 
even over matters that should remain within its own internal 
purview. For example, in the words of Mr. Armey, the Congress 
made itself "subject to the same workplace standards and 
practices as the private sector." 
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Sound good? In fact, there was a reason why Congress has 
never been subject to such laws. They are enforced by executive 
branch agencies like the Department of Labor, the Justice 
Department, and the EEOC. Private business knows how menacing 
these agencies can be, even to the point of determining workplace
composition with class-action lawsuits. 
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Already, individual Congressional offices are feeling the 
pressure to hire a "diverse" office, complete with quotas and 
affirmative action. This not only wrecks staff morale and 
cripples efforts to repeal these laws. It subjects Congressional 
offices to a subtle and corrupt domination by the president 
himself. Already, some offices have been pressured to end morning 
prayers for fear of violating the first amendment. 
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Since the New Deal, we have lived under an imperial 
executive that contradicts both the letter and spirit of the 
original Constitution (which instituted Congressional supremacy).
With these two acts--the line-item veto and regulation of 
legislative offices--executive-branch control is enhanced to 
dangerous new levels. 
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Mr. Armey claims that the agricultural bill represents 
revolutionary change, but here again is more bluster than 
substance. The farm bill merely changed the regulations to ensure 
agribusiness subsidies continue to flow in times when price 
supports has ceased to be profitable. 
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
In addition, there are the actions that Mr. Armey has pretended to 
forget about: tacitly approving the bailout of Mexico, a budget and 
power expansion for the BATF, and the authorization of privatized tax 
collection (tax farming, it was once called). Each case represents an 
increase in the degree and scope of federal government power, exactly 
the opposite of what this Congress promised. 
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Now it appears that the leadership is accepting the newest 
conventional wisdom of media-land: Congress needs to pass some 
more legislation before the election to impress voters. Thus the 
leadership is conspiring to give us Hillary-lite in the form of 
new health insurance mandates and regulations, as well as an 
egregious increase in the minimum wage, guaranteed to raise the 
unemployment rate after this session closes. 
 <BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
If Bob Dole deserves the aspersions being cast upon him, so 
does the entire Congressional leadership. If voters give them a 
whop on the nose this November, it won't be undeserved. It's time 
for men like Mr. Armey to 'fess up, so their coming political 
losses won't be interpreted as a verdict on the public's view 
that most of what the federal government does has outlived its 
usefulness. 
<P> 

<I> 
Llewellyn H. Rockwell, Jr., is president of the Ludwig von Mises  
Institute in Auburn, Alabama.<I>
<br>
<P><P>
</blockquote></blockquote>

<P> <br>
