An Insight Look
 By Thomas A. Schatz


The Oklahoma City tragedy was felt by every American.  Sympathy for 
the victims, particularly the innocent children, has hit hard.  The 
outpouring of emotion has been and will continue to be overwhelming, 
because Americans care and will do anything and give everything they 
can to help the victims and their families.

All indications are that some members of right-wing militias were 
involved.  Yet, even before all the victims were accounted for and 
properly mourned, some Americans began the "guilt-by-association" 
game.  First, all members of right-wing militia groups were at fault.  
Then, conservative groups of any kind were at fault.  The president 
implicated the radio talk show hosts and called for an end to "reckless 
speech" and  "loud and angry voices," asking Americans to speak out 
against "purveyors of hatred and division."  Then, heated anti-
government rhetoric was to blame for driving the fragile and twisted 
psyches of Timothy McVeigh and his cohorts over the edge.  Carl Rowan 
blamed Senate Majority Leader Dole and House Speaker Newt Gingrich.  
Radio talk shows and conservative politicians lashed back, accusing 
liberals of using the tragedy for their own political ends.  And the Bureau 
of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms and the Federal Bureau of 
Investigation are said to share complicity because of the shootout with 
Randy Weaver and the Waco tragedy.  If anything, this display of 
shameful rhetoric and finger-pointing illustrates America's inability to 
deal with the issue of accountability.

In the wake of such sadness and grief, it is unseemly, grotesque even, for 
politicians and other public figures to make themselves the central figures 
in this tragedy.  And we should know from experience that blaming 
people simply because they hold similar views to those espoused by the 
alleged perpetrators is problematic.

Those who marched or otherwise protested against the war in Vietnam in 
an exercise of their First Amendment rights (including Bill Clinton) 
watched in horror when four students were killed at Kent State.  They 
shivered after learning of the Weather Underground campus bombings.  
After decades of oppression and discrimination, the Black Panthers 
became more militant and armed themselves.  Individuals from many of 
these movements committed crimes.  But in both of these cases, and 
many others throughout history, Americans didn't allow the misguided 
actions of a few extremists to annul or strip away the legitimate aims of 
the many.  

If one wants to make a connection between taxpayers, members of 
conservative organizations, radio talk show hosts, and the nuts that blew 
up the federal building in Oklahoma City, one must also make that same 
connection between taxpayers, members of liberal organizations, militant 
environmentalists, and the unabomber who struck again in California last 
week; or taxpayers, members of Christian fundamentalist churches, 
militant anti-abortionists, and the individual who shot the doctor in 
Pensacola, Florida.  The only real link in all of these examples is among 
the extremes on all sides and their willingness, for whatever twisted 
reasons, to resort to violence and murder.

The Oklahoma City bombing should neither be used as an excuse to 
attack the motivation of groups that seek less intrusive and more efficient 
government, nor as an excuse to perpetuate government programs which 
have simply become useless.  The budget debate, to take place 
imminently in the House and Senate, must go on.  In fact, if anything, 
that debate should be even more focused now on the proper role of 
government and the priorities that must be established for the future.

It's time to mourn, but it's also time to make decisions that will affect the 
standard of living for our children and grandchildren. 

Blunt talk, even when it seems harsh, has always been an element of 
American political discourse.  Tough action on the deficit must be taken 
on Capitol Hill.  Deliberating the merits of where and how to balance the 
budget will naturally evoke emotions on both sides of the aisle, especially 
now.  Eliminating obsolete programs, closing down entire departments, 
and reducing the massive increases in federal spending scheduled to take 
effect over the next several years is essential to the health and welfare of 
the American people and should not be inferred as a blanket abhorrence 
of all government, and certainly not the people that work within the 
system.

CAGW's Prime Cuts contains 651 recommendations to save $1.45 trillion 
over the next five years, including many that go back to the Grace 
Commission.  More than half come right from Congress' own 
Congressional Budget Office, and have been ignored.  President Clinton 
is right to call for increased law enforcement personnel and concentrated 
efforts to prevent domestic and international terrorism; that's an 
expenditure that CAGW can certainly support.  In fact, it's the sort of 
priority and choice that must be made on a much broader scale -- for 
every federal department, agency, and individual program.  That's what 
taxpayers are asking, and that's the task that must be carried out.  



To join CAGW and receive Government WasteWatch, the quarterly 
newsletter of Citizens Against Government Waste, please fill out this 
coupon and mail it with your tax-deductible contribution.

Yes, I want to join the more than 600,000 members of CAGW to fight 
Washington's wasteful ways.  I understand that $1.00 of my contribution 
entitles me to four issues of Government WasteWatch.

I have enclosed my check made payable to CAGW in the amount of:

