Keeping Congress on the Cutting Edge  
 By Thomas A. Schatz  
  
 
As the budget debate heats up on Capitol Hill, it is clear that  
sustaining the momentum of the first 100 days will be tough sledding  
for Republican leaders.  The rhetoric from the opponents of change has  
been and will continue to be harsh, unfounded, and misleading.  Inside  
the halls of Congress, the hand-wringing and whining at the undoing of  
years of wasteful and ineffective programs would make one believe the  
country will go down the drain in the near future.  
 
But taxpayers still want the revolution which began on November 8th of  
1994 with the election of a Republican Congress to be sustained.   
Outside the Washington beltway, support for reform remains strong.  
 
The truth is, without the changes being wrought in the new Congress,  
we will hit rock bottom and devastate the standard of living for  
future generations.  
 
The interest on the national debt is now almost twice as large as the  
budget deficit.  The president's budget projects a deficit of $192  
billion in fiscal year 1995 and an interest payment of $334 billion.   
In other words, without the interest on the national debt, there would  
be a surplus of $142 billion!  Over the next ten years, we could run a  
surplus every year if we did not have to pay the interest -- which  
will range from $330 billion to more than $500 billion -- and reduce  
the debt by $1,355 billion.  That, of course, is assuming that  
interest rates remain as projected.  If they go higher (remember a  
prime rate of nearly 21 percent in late 1980?), the results could be a  
Mexico-type disaster, where other countries will have to bail out the  
United States.  
 
But the forces of the status quo are doing everything in their power  
to fight the knights in shining armor -- both Republicans and  
Democrats -- who are rescuing the future of our nation.  
 
Here's how the truth is being twisted:  
 
During the debate on the balanced budget amendment (BBA), the  
naysayers claimed that Social Security must be exempt.  The real  
threat to Social Security, as expressed by Sen. John Breaux, a  
Democrat from Louisiana, is if it is not exempt.  Keeping the program  
out of the BBA would give Congress the opportunity to add any program  
it wanted to "Social Security," which would undermine the basic old  
age, survivors and disability payments now provided to beneficiaries.   
For example, Congress could set up a special fund for student aid  
under Social Security, or for farmers, or veterans.  Already, Social  
Security disability funds are being used for cash payments to drug  
addicts and alcoholics, a well-publicized abuse of our tax dollars.   
Do we really want to leave that program untouchable under a balanced  
budget amendment?  And if a program is included in the exemption under  
Social Security, it is likely to expand dramatically as has been the  
practice in Washington.  The red herring of Social Security in the  
debate over the BBA was the first major volley in the battle to turn  
around the effort to eliminate the waste and the deficit.  
 
Social Security doesn't have to be involved at all in the budget  
debate: Representatives Jerry Solomon (R-N.Y.) and Mark Neumann (R- 
Wisc.) have proposed a budget that would truly remove Social Security  
from the furor of how to rein in federal spending.  Their plan would  
not only balance the budget in five years by freezing all spending at  
current levels, it would eliminate the debt in thirty years by  
increasing spending by one percent less than revenues through the year  
2025 in their budget proposal.  Their list of options includes $70  
billion more than is necessary to balance the budget within five  
years.  
 
According to opponents, the provisions of the House welfare bill will  
result in millions of children being left in the streets, and massive  
homelessness and starvation.  But these alarmists failed to note that  
spending more than $5 trillion since 1965 in the war against poverty  
has not solved the problem.  The House bill moves in a new direction,  
which is apparently too much for the defenders of the status quo to  
handle.  
 
Spending on welfare will increase by only $60 billion less than  
projected in President Clinton's FY 1996 budget.  The school lunch  
program will increase by four percent per year instead of six percent  
per year over the next five years.  This is fiscal restraint, not  
heartlessness.  Claiming that children will be starving on the streets  
is just a little too melodramatic to hold water.  
 
The truth will win out, and the waste will be cut.  But the job is far  
from over.  We must preserve the future for our children and  
grandchildren.  
 
  
  
To join CAGW and receive Government WasteWatch, the quarterly  
newsletter of Citizens Against Government Waste, please fill out this  
coupon and mail it with your tax-deductible contribution.  
  
Yes, I want to join the more than 600,000 members of CAGW to fight  
Washington's wasteful ways.  I understand that $1.00 of my  
contribution entitles me to four issues of Government WasteWatch.  
  
