DENVER INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT:  WHAT WENT WRONG 
 By: Thomas Schatz, President, Citizens Against Government Waste 
 

This past March, the Council for Citizens Against Government Waste 
(CCAGW) held a regional taxpayers' conference in Denver.  It's ironic 
that the leading group fighting waste had to fly into a prime example 
of why America is currently strangled by a $4.8 trillion national debt 
-- the new Denver International Airport (DIA).  Assessing what went 
wrong with the Denver Airport is critically important.    

According to the House Appropriations Subcommittee on Transportation 
and the General Accounting Office (GAO), $685 million will be spent by 
the federal government on the Denver Airport through fiscal year (FY) 
2001.  Every single dollar of this $685 million will be wasted.   This 
is not an overstatement because this airport was not needed.  Plain 
and simple.  Stapleton Airport could have been upgraded to accommodate 
any larger planes that might land in Denver in the future.  Extending 
runways at Stapleton would have been inexpensive and quick.  But 
because this country has an edifice complex, a new structure had to be 
built.  When a family has a tight budget, they don't go to the opera 
or drive an expensive car.  The federal government has to realize that 
we cannot afford luxuries, especially when there isn't a need for such 
a luxury. 
 
Just as the federal government has become adept at deficits, so will 
DIA.  The GAO projected a cumulative operating deficit of  $230 
million by its February opening.  
 
The DIA is government waste -- at its worst.  DIA is not an example of 
pork-barrel waste.  The kind of government waste that occurred in 
Denver is more insidious.  The back-room politicking and the 
misinformation that occurred is an embarrassment to the federal 
government as well as the local government.   

The new 53-square-mile airport is larger than the District of 
Columbia.  The airport is 25 miles from downtown.  A cab ride will 
increase from $7 to Stapleton to $50 to DIA.  There is currently no 
supporting infrastructure to serve the new airport.  Access to rental 
cars and hotels is extremely difficult.  These are the general 
problems.  Here are the specific problems with DIA.   

The public was shut out of the process, and no user or public needs 
were defined or documented.  The politicians limited the vote to the 
core city, or about 10 percent of airport users.  Denver is a 
relatively small city of 460,000, down six percent in population in 
the 1980's.  Denver is not among the top 400 cities worldwide, yet the 
city set out to build the "World's Largest Airport."  Only about 70 
gates out of 200 are actually in operation at DIA.  A dozen or so 
gates are not in operation because of a lack of covered jetways.  Thus 
incoming flights are delayed.  
 
The Denver Airport has come to symbolize the reckless manner in which 
federal construction is carried out in America.  Because the airport 
is eligible for formula grants, money is not awarded based on merit.  
If this were a project that was being funded by a private financial 
institution, more scrutiny would have gone into the planning, 
implementation and construction of this airport.  The federal 
government should not be providing an open checkbook for construction 
based on the fact that it creates jobs.   The $685 million that the 
federal government will spend through 2001 could mean $1,489 in tax 
relief for every resident of Denver. 

There was no need for a new airport in Denver.  During the 1986-1989 
planning period, Denver's share of the U.S. air travel market dropped 
53 percent -- from 3.8 percent in 1986 to 2.57 percent in 1990 (1994 
is estimated at 2.6 percent).  However, during those years, the 
Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) and Denver forecast that DIA 
would be the fastest-growing airport in the U.S., with 50 million 
passengers by 1995, and the second-busiest by 2000.  According to the 
Air Transportation Association (ATA), Denver also dropped from 8th to 
19th in U.S air cargo tonnage during the past five years.  The ATA has 
never included Denver in the "Table of Top 30 U.S. Domestic Air Travel 
Markets."  Top listings are high population cities and vacation 
centers.  Denver is neither. 
 
According to Mayor Pea in Volume I of the 1987 Airport Report, 
"Stapleton had the best history of low delays.  Stapleton was ranked 
number five in traffic and number nine in delays."  The Pea 
administration in 1988 decided to trash Stapleton, then one of the 
best airports in the world, to build a totally new airport for $1.5 
billion.  Mr. Pea's 1989 Airport Report claimed "Stapleton was grid 
locking the nation," and by 1996 "is expected to lead the delay list 
with 158,000 hours annually."   Federal funding for DIA was to be $500 
million, and the "Stapleton site would be disposed of over several 
years to raise more than a half-billion dollars."   The projected cost 
is now more than $4.9 billion.   

The bottom line is:  DIA is expensive and unnecessary.  The new Denver 
Airport should not have been built.  The way that it was built is an 
embarrassment to representative government at all levels.   
 
What will the real losses be at DIA?  How soon will the losses eat up 
the reserves set aside to pay the bondholders?  Who will pay for the 
bailout -- the city and county of Denver, Colorado's taxpayers, or the 
federal government?  Who will be left holding the bag when this 
airport fails?  The American taxpayer will be left in the lurch again. 
 

 
To join CAGW and receive Government WasteWatch, the quarterly 
newsletter of Citizens Against Government Waste, please fill out this 
coupon and mail it with your tax-deductible contribution. 
 
Yes, I want to join the more than 600,000 members of CAGW to fight 
Washington's wasteful ways.  I understand that $1.00 of my 
contribution entitles me to four issues of Government WasteWatch. 
 
